5
00:00:40,832 --> 00:00:42,368
- You're on TV in New York, too.
- No, no.

6
00:00:42,543 --> 00:00:44,751
- Yes, you are.
- Am I really? Are you serious?

7
00:00:44,878 --> 00:00:47,120
- Yeah, they got you in New York.
- God.

8
00:00:51,134 --> 00:00:53,296
I'm gonna let you
put it in your own ear.

9
00:00:53,428 --> 00:00:54,635
- Really?
- It's a talk back.

10
00:00:54,763 --> 00:00:58,552
- They're going to talk to you.
- This is not the real thing, right?

11
00:00:58,684 --> 00:01:00,016
You just want a picture of me now?

12
00:01:00,185 --> 00:01:02,893
- They're going to sit you here first.
- God.

13
00:01:06,900 --> 00:01:08,732
You need to tell me
where the restroom is, too,

14
00:01:08,860 --> 00:01:10,146
cos I'm deathly ill, actually,

15
00:01:10,320 --> 00:01:11,902
and ready to throw up
at any moment, so...

16
00:01:12,030 --> 00:01:16,365
- It's right across the hall.
- Great. I'm not joking.

17
00:01:24,376 --> 00:01:27,619
We're ready to go, gentlemen.
New York's waiting for a shot of him.

18
00:01:58,744 --> 00:02:02,454
If you see in my eyes,
I've been crying just a little bit.

19
00:02:02,581 --> 00:02:05,619
And it seems really ridiculous
because I've never met the man.

20
00:02:05,751 --> 00:02:11,543
I know life is ephemeral,
but I just, you know,

21
00:02:11,673 --> 00:02:14,586
I expected him to be around
a little longer.

22
00:02:14,718 --> 00:02:17,005
Pretty sure everybody did,
but, you know...

23
00:02:17,137 --> 00:02:21,131
The thing I'm using right now,
an iMac, he made.

24
00:02:21,266 --> 00:02:25,010
He made the iMac.
He made the Macbook.

25
00:02:25,145 --> 00:02:28,388
He made the Macbook Pro.
He made the Macbook Air.

26
00:02:28,523 --> 00:02:32,187
He made the iPhone.
He made the iPod.

27
00:02:34,029 --> 00:02:38,774
Yeah, he's made the iPod Touch.
He's made everything.

28
00:02:44,289 --> 00:02:49,535
<i>♪ Hey, Mr Tambourine Man
Play a song for me</i>

29
00:02:49,711 --> 00:02:54,672
<i>♪ I'm not sleepy
And there's no place I'm going to</i>

30
00:02:55,634 --> 00:03:01,471
<i>♪ Hey, Mr Tambourine Man
Play a song for me</i>

31
00:03:01,598 --> 00:03:06,889
<i>♪ In the jingle jangle morning
I'll come following you</i>

32
00:03:07,896 --> 00:03:12,061
It's not often that the whole
planet seems to feel a loss together,

33
00:03:12,192 --> 00:03:14,058
but after the death of Steve Jobs,

34
00:03:14,194 --> 00:03:17,153
co-founder of Apple
and singular dreamer,

35
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:20,364
all day, we watched
as there was a kind of global wake.

36
00:03:20,492 --> 00:03:24,532
<i>On Facebook, millions changing
their profiles to the Apple logo.</i>

37
00:03:24,663 --> 00:03:28,156
<i>A kind of black armband,
a gesture of gratitude.</i>

38
00:03:28,375 --> 00:03:32,540
<i>We've been monitoring
the hashtag "thankyousteve."</i>

39
00:03:32,671 --> 00:03:34,378
<i>My favorite tweet last night</i>

40
00:03:34,589 --> 00:03:39,175
<i>was four simple letters
simply saying, "iSad."</i>

41
00:03:52,566 --> 00:03:53,852
Hi.

42
00:03:57,988 --> 00:04:01,152
<i>When Steve Jobs died,
I was mystified.</i>

43
00:04:01,283 --> 00:04:05,072
<i>What accounted for the grief of
millions of people who didn't know him?</i>

44
00:04:05,203 --> 00:04:08,571
<i>I'd seen it with John Lennon
and Martin Luther king,</i>

45
00:04:08,707 --> 00:04:12,291
<i>but Steve Jobs wasn't a singer
or a civil-rights leader.</i>

46
00:04:13,503 --> 00:04:16,667
Many commentators were surprised

47
00:04:16,798 --> 00:04:21,884
by the intensity and the power
of this wave of emotion.

48
00:04:22,012 --> 00:04:27,007
What was it?
And I think it was truly love.

49
00:04:27,142 --> 00:04:33,184
Jobs has proven to be the one
and only person in the world

50
00:04:33,315 --> 00:04:38,606
who can create
technology products that people love.

51
00:04:41,239 --> 00:04:42,901
Wall-E.

52
00:04:43,784 --> 00:04:47,198
<i>I love "Wall-E,"
a film Jobs's Pixar produced,</i>

53
00:04:47,329 --> 00:04:49,537
<i>and I love my iPhone,</i>

54
00:04:49,748 --> 00:04:54,038
<i>but the grief for Jobs seemed to go
beyond the products he left behind.</i>

55
00:04:54,169 --> 00:04:57,583
<i>We mourned the man himself,
but why?</i>

56
00:04:57,714 --> 00:05:01,879
<i>Behind the scenes, Jobs could be
ruthless, deceitful and cruel.</i>

57
00:05:02,010 --> 00:05:07,301
<i>Yet he won our hearts by convincing us
that Apple represented a higher ideal.</i>

58
00:05:07,432 --> 00:05:11,676
<i>It was not like other companies.
It was different.</i>

59
00:05:13,730 --> 00:05:18,600
Good morning and welcome to Apple's
1984 annual shareholders' meeting.

60
00:05:18,735 --> 00:05:21,148
I'd like to open the meeting
with part of an old poem,

61
00:05:21,279 --> 00:05:24,443
about a 20-year-old poem, by Dylan.
That's Bob Dylan.

62
00:05:26,493 --> 00:05:29,702
"Come writers and critics
who prophesize with your pens

63
00:05:29,830 --> 00:05:32,413
and keep your eyes wide,
the chance won't come again."

64
00:05:32,582 --> 00:05:35,290
"And don't speak too soon
for the wheel's still in spin

65
00:05:35,460 --> 00:05:37,827
and there's no telling
who that it's naming."

66
00:05:37,963 --> 00:05:42,708
"For the loser now will be later to win,
for the times, they are a-changing."

67
00:05:42,926 --> 00:05:46,840
<i>Jobs loved Dylan
maybe because he wasn’t just one thing.</i>

68
00:05:47,013 --> 00:05:51,428
<i>He was a storyteller who could
be whatever we wanted him to be.</i>

69
00:05:52,644 --> 00:05:55,978
I don't even what know what
<i>All Along The Watchtower</i> means.

70
00:05:56,106 --> 00:05:58,393
I think it is one of
the most beautiful, haunting,

71
00:05:58,525 --> 00:06:04,317
brilliant pieces of poetry ever.
And to me, it's like Steve.

72
00:06:05,866 --> 00:06:09,109
"There must be some way
out of here, said the..."

73
00:06:09,244 --> 00:06:10,244
What is it?

74
00:06:10,287 --> 00:06:11,903
<i>Said the Joker to the Thief.</i>

75
00:06:12,247 --> 00:06:13,613
He's both.

76
00:06:28,555 --> 00:06:31,923
<i>♪ "There must be
Some way out of here"</i>

77
00:06:32,058 --> 00:06:34,015
<i>♪ Said the joker to the thief</i>

78
00:06:35,145 --> 00:06:38,559
<i>♪ There's too much confusion</i>

79
00:06:38,732 --> 00:06:40,564
<i>♪ I can't get no relief</i>

80
00:06:41,943 --> 00:06:44,651
<i>♪ Businessmen, they drink my wine</i>

81
00:06:44,779 --> 00:06:48,193
<i>♪ Plowmen dig my earth</i>

82
00:06:48,325 --> 00:06:51,363
<i>♪ None of them along the line</i>

83
00:06:51,494 --> 00:06:54,658
<i>♪ Know what any of it is worth</i>

84
00:07:31,868 --> 00:07:34,030
<i>There's something going on
here in life</i>

85
00:07:34,162 --> 00:07:37,997
<i>beyond just a job and a family
and career.</i>

86
00:07:38,124 --> 00:07:40,867
<i>There's another side of the coin.</i>

87
00:07:44,339 --> 00:07:45,705
<i>It's the same thing</i>

88
00:07:45,882 --> 00:07:50,217
<i>that causes people to want to be poets
instead of bankers.</i>

89
00:07:51,930 --> 00:07:57,301
<i>And I think that that same spirit
can be put into products.</i>

90
00:07:57,435 --> 00:07:59,893
<i>And those products can be manufactured
and given to people,</i>

91
00:08:00,021 --> 00:08:02,354
<i>and they can sense that spirit.</i>

92
00:08:05,652 --> 00:08:09,111
<i>A computer is a straightforward,
everyday machine.</i>

93
00:08:09,239 --> 00:08:11,982
<i>A simple way of studying
the principle of how it works</i>

94
00:08:12,117 --> 00:08:15,235
<i>is that a computer is quite dead.</i>

95
00:08:15,370 --> 00:08:18,408
<i>It can do nothing without
someone to give instructions.</i>

96
00:08:20,375 --> 00:08:23,539
<i>When I was growing up,
computers weren't something to love.</i>

97
00:08:23,670 --> 00:08:25,457
<i>They were something to fear.</i>

98
00:08:25,588 --> 00:08:29,878
<i>They were huge, impersonal,
made by faceless corporations.</i>

99
00:08:30,010 --> 00:08:33,128
<i>But for Jobs, it was different.</i>

100
00:08:33,263 --> 00:08:36,176
I saw my first computer
when I was 12 at NASA.

101
00:08:36,307 --> 00:08:39,641
<i>We had a local NASA center
nearby. It was a terminal,</i>

102
00:08:39,811 --> 00:08:42,178
<i>which was connected
to a big computer somewhere.</i>

103
00:08:42,313 --> 00:08:45,101
This is one of the consoles
they might be using in the future.

104
00:08:45,275 --> 00:08:47,437
It looks very much like
just a regular typewriter.

105
00:08:47,569 --> 00:08:49,026
Too often the equipment of the past

106
00:08:49,154 --> 00:08:51,020
has sort of been designed
for other machines.

107
00:08:51,156 --> 00:08:52,317
They're really not for people.

108
00:08:52,449 --> 00:08:57,035
I saw my second computer a few
years later, the Hewlett-Packard 9100.

109
00:08:57,162 --> 00:08:59,950
The 9100 computing calculator.

110
00:09:00,081 --> 00:09:05,076
It was very large. Had a very small
cathode ray tube on it for display.

111
00:09:05,211 --> 00:09:08,830
And I got a chance to play with
one of those maybe in 1968.

112
00:09:08,965 --> 00:09:10,501
<i>I started going up</i>

113
00:09:10,633 --> 00:09:13,751
<i>to Hewlett-Packard's Palo Alto
research lab every Tuesday night,</i>

114
00:09:13,887 --> 00:09:18,052
and I spent every spare moment I had
trying to write programs for it.

115
00:09:18,183 --> 00:09:19,264
I was so fascinated by this.

116
00:09:21,478 --> 00:09:23,936
We have a pointing device
called a mouse.

117
00:09:24,064 --> 00:09:25,646
I don't know why we call it a mouse.

118
00:09:25,815 --> 00:09:30,185
<i>By 1968, Stanford's
Doug Engelbart, inventor of the mouse,</i>

119
00:09:30,320 --> 00:09:31,856
<i>was asking new questions</i>

120
00:09:31,988 --> 00:09:36,232
<i>about the essential nature of our
changing relationship with computers.</i>

121
00:09:36,367 --> 00:09:39,986
If in your office,
you as an intellectual worker

122
00:09:40,121 --> 00:09:42,955
were supplied with a computer display

123
00:09:43,083 --> 00:09:47,202
backed up by a computer
that was alive for you all day

124
00:09:47,337 --> 00:09:51,581
and was instantly responsible,
responsive,

125
00:09:51,716 --> 00:09:53,924
instantly responsive
to every action you had,

126
00:09:54,094 --> 00:09:56,051
how much value
could you derive from that?

127
00:09:56,221 --> 00:10:00,181
<i>We needed a guide to help us
navigate this new relationship.</i>

128
00:10:03,228 --> 00:10:08,269
<i>My whole adult life has been spent
building personal computers.</i>

129
00:10:08,399 --> 00:10:13,440
<i>So, the history of my vocation
and my avocations</i>

130
00:10:13,571 --> 00:10:16,905
<i>and, you know,
my growing up are all the same,</i>

131
00:10:17,075 --> 00:10:19,738
and it's very hard
to separate one from the other.

132
00:10:29,045 --> 00:10:31,879
<i>I come from a place called
Silicon Valley, California,</i>

133
00:10:32,006 --> 00:10:34,999
<i>and you'll find there are
a lot of electronics kits around.</i>

134
00:10:35,135 --> 00:10:39,049
<i>My electronics teacher realized
that I had a lot of computer ability</i>

135
00:10:39,180 --> 00:10:41,547
<i>that went beyond anything he could
possibly teach me in school.</i>

136
00:10:41,683 --> 00:10:45,222
He knew that as long as I was in class,
I was just going to sit around,

137
00:10:45,353 --> 00:10:47,185
playing pranks on the other students

138
00:10:47,397 --> 00:10:49,764
like wrapping little hair wires
around certain circuits

139
00:10:49,899 --> 00:10:52,141
so when they plugged in their radio,
it would blow up.

140
00:10:58,241 --> 00:10:59,823
<i>As hard as I think about it,</i>

141
00:10:59,993 --> 00:11:02,406
<i>I don't think I ever had one friend
who was not one of the tech kids.</i>

142
00:11:03,955 --> 00:11:07,448
<i>I met Woz when I was maybe
12 years old, 13 years old.</i>

143
00:11:07,584 --> 00:11:10,292
<i>He was the first person I met
that knew more electronics than I did.</i>

144
00:11:10,420 --> 00:11:14,755
And one of the things that Woz and I did
was we built blue boxes.

145
00:11:19,095 --> 00:11:20,961
<i>One day I picked up a magazine,</i>

146
00:11:21,097 --> 00:11:25,341
and I started reading a story
about phone phreaks and blue boxes.

147
00:11:27,395 --> 00:11:29,557
<i>When phone phreaks
have a convention,</i>

148
00:11:29,689 --> 00:11:33,433
<i>as they did in the ballroom
of a seedy New York hotel lately,</i>

149
00:11:33,568 --> 00:11:38,188
<i>masks are given out at the door.
People don't give their right names.</i>

150
00:11:38,364 --> 00:11:43,280
The blue box was a little device that
put special tones into anybody's phone

151
00:11:43,411 --> 00:11:46,700
and those tones would connect you
anywhere you wanted.

152
00:11:46,831 --> 00:11:49,619
<i>Halfway through reading this,
I called Steve Jobs over</i>

153
00:11:49,792 --> 00:11:52,751
<i>and started reading it to him
over the phone.</i>

154
00:11:52,962 --> 00:11:55,830
There's a way to fool
the entire telephone system

155
00:11:56,007 --> 00:11:58,169
into thinking you were
a telephone computer

156
00:11:58,301 --> 00:12:01,294
and to open up itself and let you call
anywhere in the world for free.

157
00:12:01,429 --> 00:12:05,139
<i>You could call from a pay phone,
go to White Plains, New York,</i>

158
00:12:05,266 --> 00:12:06,757
<i>take a satellite to Europe.</i>

159
00:12:06,893 --> 00:12:09,476
<i>And you'd go around the world
and call the pay phone next door.</i>

160
00:12:09,646 --> 00:12:11,729
<i>Shout in the phone,
be about 30 seconds,</i>

161
00:12:11,856 --> 00:12:13,597
<i>it'd come out the other end
of the other phone.</i>

162
00:12:13,775 --> 00:12:17,519
And he's like, "Hello,"
There's a lag and, "Hello, how are you?"

163
00:12:17,654 --> 00:12:19,361
"I'm fine." You know?

164
00:12:19,489 --> 00:12:22,903
<i>Why, one might wonder,
would someone want to do that?</i>

165
00:12:23,076 --> 00:12:25,363
<i>To rip off the phone company.</i>

166
00:12:25,495 --> 00:12:27,657
And these were illegal, I have to add.

167
00:12:29,916 --> 00:12:33,500
<i>In college, I had a blue box
of my own. It was important</i>

168
00:12:33,628 --> 00:12:37,212
<i>because long-distance phone calls
were really expensive back then.</i>

169
00:12:38,633 --> 00:12:41,842
<i>It was also a way
of sticking it to the man.</i>

170
00:12:42,095 --> 00:12:45,714
<i>This would become an important
selling point for Jobs, too,</i>

171
00:12:45,848 --> 00:12:49,558
<i>even as he left
the technical work to others.</i>

172
00:12:49,686 --> 00:12:51,643
<i>Well, I had this blue box design.</i>

173
00:12:51,771 --> 00:12:54,058
<i>I did a trick in there
that I've never done that good a trick</i>

174
00:12:54,190 --> 00:12:55,647
<i>in any other design in my life.</i>

175
00:12:55,775 --> 00:12:59,735
<i>And Steve Jobs said,
"Hey, why don't we sell them?"</i>

176
00:12:59,862 --> 00:13:02,229
<i>You know, you rapidly run
out of people you want to call,</i>

177
00:13:02,365 --> 00:13:05,449
<i>but it was the magic that two teenagers</i>

178
00:13:05,576 --> 00:13:08,284
<i>could build this box
for $100 worth of parts</i>

179
00:13:08,413 --> 00:13:13,533
<i>and control hundreds of billions
of dollars of infrastructure</i>

180
00:13:13,668 --> 00:13:16,502
<i>in the entire telephone network
in the whole world.</i>

181
00:13:17,839 --> 00:13:22,755
We could sort of influence the world,
you know?

182
00:13:22,885 --> 00:13:24,547
Control it, in the case of blue boxes,

183
00:13:24,721 --> 00:13:27,134
but something much more powerful
than controlling.

184
00:13:27,265 --> 00:13:32,226
Influencing, in the case of Apple.
And they're very closely related.

185
00:13:32,353 --> 00:13:33,810
I really do, to this day,

186
00:13:33,938 --> 00:13:37,147
feel that if we hadn't had had
those blue box experiences,

187
00:13:37,358 --> 00:13:39,645
there never would have been
an Apple computer.

188
00:13:39,777 --> 00:13:41,939
<i>I think Jobs
was always a storyteller.</i>

189
00:13:42,113 --> 00:13:45,948
There was always this sense
that he was constructing a persona.

190
00:13:47,327 --> 00:13:50,070
<i>The first time I sat down
with him to work on a story,</i>

191
00:13:50,204 --> 00:13:52,321
he immediately asked me
if I had read.

192
00:13:52,457 --> 00:13:57,577
<i>Thomas Kuhn's "The Structure
of Scientific Revolutions."</i>

193
00:13:57,712 --> 00:14:00,455
<i>I think he was assimilating
into this personality,</i>

194
00:14:00,590 --> 00:14:02,923
<i>this notion that he had found in Kuhn.</i>

195
00:14:03,092 --> 00:14:06,210
<i>The random result
that eventually creates</i>

196
00:14:06,346 --> 00:14:08,963
a paradigm shift where everybody
one morning wakes up,

197
00:14:09,140 --> 00:14:10,881
and they think the new way.

198
00:14:11,017 --> 00:14:15,136
<i>And I believe that he thought
that he was a paradigm shifter.</i>

199
00:14:15,271 --> 00:14:19,231
<i>That was part of his story. He wanted
to have a foot in both worlds.</i>

200
00:14:19,359 --> 00:14:22,943
<i>He wanted to be the renegade,
but he also wanted to be legit.</i>

201
00:14:24,989 --> 00:14:29,654
<i>This is the video deposition
of Steven P Jobs.</i>

202
00:14:29,786 --> 00:14:33,746
We are on the record at 9:22am.

203
00:14:33,873 --> 00:14:38,243
Can we just sort of briefly go over
your employment history after 1973?

204
00:14:39,879 --> 00:14:45,546
I was employed by Atari,
a maker of video games.

205
00:14:47,387 --> 00:14:51,757
- What timeframe?
- I don't know. Early '70s.

206
00:15:04,278 --> 00:15:08,363
Creativity is a lot about anarchy.

207
00:15:10,952 --> 00:15:13,410
<i>I had been in the video-game
business two years</i>

208
00:15:13,538 --> 00:15:18,533
and our corporate culture
was really "work hard, play hard."

209
00:15:18,668 --> 00:15:20,751
<i>The true original sin of Apple</i>

210
00:15:20,878 --> 00:15:23,746
literally takes place
before the company is founded.

211
00:15:23,881 --> 00:15:27,465
<i>Jobs had left Reed College
and now he was back in Silicon Valley.</i>

212
00:15:27,593 --> 00:15:29,676
<i>Woz was working at HP.</i>

213
00:15:29,804 --> 00:15:31,215
<i>I was such a nerd.</i>

214
00:15:31,347 --> 00:15:34,340
<i>When I finished designing calculators
at Hewlett-Packard in the daytime,</i>

215
00:15:34,475 --> 00:15:36,182
<i>I would work on my own little projects.</i>

216
00:15:36,310 --> 00:15:38,518
<i>I saw "Pong" in a bowling alley,
and I said,</i>

217
00:15:38,646 --> 00:15:41,605
<i>"I know logic design,
and I know electronics of televisions."</i>

218
00:15:41,732 --> 00:15:46,773
<i>"I'll use my home TV, snake a wire in,"
and I built myself a "Pong."</i>

219
00:15:46,904 --> 00:15:48,611
Steve came back from Reed College

220
00:15:48,739 --> 00:15:51,322
and saw that I had built
my own <i>Pong</i> game.

221
00:15:51,451 --> 00:15:54,239
<i>And so that gave him the idea
to go down to Atari.</i>

222
00:15:54,370 --> 00:15:56,737
<i>And he went down,
and he showed them the board</i>

223
00:15:56,914 --> 00:15:58,450
<i>and he wound up with a job.</i>

224
00:15:58,583 --> 00:16:01,747
Steve came in and said,
in typical Steve Jobs fashion,

225
00:16:01,878 --> 00:16:03,710
"I'm not going to leave
until you hire me."

226
00:16:03,838 --> 00:16:10,506
<i>And I really appreciated his intensity.
He had one speed. Full on.</i>

227
00:16:10,636 --> 00:16:13,970
<i>I had one little project
that everyone kept turning down.</i>

228
00:16:14,098 --> 00:16:15,805
<i>It was a project called "Breakout."</i>

229
00:16:15,933 --> 00:16:19,017
<i>And finally I said,
"Steve, hey, do this for me."</i>

230
00:16:19,145 --> 00:16:20,431
In the back of my mind,

231
00:16:20,563 --> 00:16:26,480
I knew that Woz was coming over all
the time after working at HP all day,

232
00:16:26,611 --> 00:16:30,230
and I thought,
"OK, I'll put Steve on the night shift."

233
00:16:30,448 --> 00:16:33,486
"Woz will come over. I'll get
two Steves for the price of one."

234
00:16:33,618 --> 00:16:37,407
<i>Steve said, "Nolan Bushnell
of Atari wants another game built."</i>

235
00:16:37,538 --> 00:16:39,495
<i>But we only had four days, Steve said.</i>

236
00:16:39,624 --> 00:16:42,458
<i>When a game is made out of chips
and it's not a program,</i>

237
00:16:42,585 --> 00:16:45,749
<i>four days is, like, impossible.
This is months' worth of work.</i>

238
00:16:47,757 --> 00:16:48,793
<i>I did the entire design,</i>

239
00:16:48,925 --> 00:16:51,542
<i>and then Steve would breadboard
my design for a little while.</i>

240
00:16:52,553 --> 00:16:56,968
<i>We were up four days and nights
non-stop. Both got mononucleosis.</i>

241
00:16:57,099 --> 00:17:00,012
<i>And we got "Breakout" delivered
to Atari, and they paid for it.</i>

242
00:17:04,607 --> 00:17:07,645
<i>Later on,
Woz and I were out to dinner.</i>

243
00:17:07,777 --> 00:17:10,144
He was talking about <i>Breakout,</i>

244
00:17:10,321 --> 00:17:13,530
and I said, "Well, you know,
you guys got paid pretty well for it."

245
00:17:13,658 --> 00:17:16,275
He looked at me puzzled, and I said,

246
00:17:16,410 --> 00:17:19,574
"Yeah, I mean,
you did such a good job."

247
00:17:19,705 --> 00:17:24,791
"I think there was at least
a $5,000 bonus that you guys got."

248
00:17:24,919 --> 00:17:28,788
So, yeah, he was paid $7,000,
and he told me that we were paid $700,

249
00:17:28,923 --> 00:17:30,915
and he wrote me a check for $350.

250
00:17:32,134 --> 00:17:34,217
<i>You know, and that hurts
because we were friends.</i>

251
00:17:34,387 --> 00:17:36,549
<i>And do you do that to a friend?</i>

252
00:17:36,681 --> 00:17:39,765
<i>If he'd said, "I need the money,"
I would have said, "Take it all."</i>

253
00:17:39,892 --> 00:17:42,509
<i>I was happy to be on the project.</i>

254
00:17:42,645 --> 00:17:45,228
I think that Steve...

255
00:17:47,316 --> 00:17:50,354
was very driven

256
00:17:50,486 --> 00:17:57,279
and would very often take
shortcuts to achieve his goals.

257
00:18:02,456 --> 00:18:06,416
♪ Then in time we'll tell who has fell

258
00:18:06,544 --> 00:18:09,537
<i>♪ And who's been left behind</i>

259
00:18:09,672 --> 00:18:12,915
<i>♪ When you go your way
And I go mine</i>

260
00:18:15,928 --> 00:18:19,092
<i>Apple was a sitcom.
It was a 30-year sitcom.</i>

261
00:18:19,223 --> 00:18:21,681
And Steve was the main character.

262
00:18:25,187 --> 00:18:28,396
<i>This was written in December 1976.</i>

263
00:18:28,524 --> 00:18:32,734
In fact it starts out saying,
"Who's Apple," so that was very early.

264
00:18:35,281 --> 00:18:39,241
<i>He and Woz came in.
Steve had long hair down his back.</i>

265
00:18:39,410 --> 00:18:44,371
<i>He had a Ho Chi Minh beard,
cutoffs, Birkenstocks.</i>

266
00:18:44,498 --> 00:18:48,367
And Wozniak was maybe a little bit
upscale from that, but not much.

267
00:18:48,502 --> 00:18:50,619
I used to like Intel's advertising,

268
00:18:50,755 --> 00:18:53,748
So I called them up one day,
and I said, "Who does your advertising?"

269
00:18:53,883 --> 00:18:56,796
They said, "Well, Regis McKenna."
"What's a Regis McKenna?"

270
00:18:56,927 --> 00:18:58,759
They said, "No, it's a person."

271
00:18:58,888 --> 00:19:02,677
<i>Wozniak had a technical article
on the Apple II.</i>

272
00:19:02,808 --> 00:19:05,767
<i>He wanted us to try to get it
placed into a magazine.</i>

273
00:19:05,895 --> 00:19:10,265
Nobody could read it. It was
all technical jargon and so forth.

274
00:19:10,441 --> 00:19:12,353
<i>And so I told him
I'd have to rewrite it,</i>

275
00:19:12,485 --> 00:19:14,522
<i>and he wasn't happy about that.</i>

276
00:19:14,654 --> 00:19:16,771
He said, "No one's going to rewrite
my stuff."

277
00:19:16,906 --> 00:19:18,863
I said, "Well,
then there's nothing I can do for you",

278
00:19:18,991 --> 00:19:20,107
so you might as well leave."

279
00:19:20,284 --> 00:19:23,527
<i>Steve called back,
and he pretty much convinced me</i>

280
00:19:23,663 --> 00:19:25,780
<i>that he would be the person
that we'd be dealing with</i>

281
00:19:25,915 --> 00:19:28,874
and that Wozniak would be designing
and building things,

282
00:19:29,001 --> 00:19:30,867
which is the way it happens
in most businesses.

283
00:19:31,003 --> 00:19:32,710
The engineers are more back room

284
00:19:32,922 --> 00:19:36,666
and you work with either the
entrepreneur or the marketing people.

285
00:19:38,094 --> 00:19:40,461
<i>Did you think early on
that Steve could be the guy?</i>

286
00:19:40,596 --> 00:19:44,260
Oh, definitely. You just had to spend
a few minutes with him and you knew it.

287
00:19:44,433 --> 00:19:45,799
<i>He had the ability</i>

288
00:19:45,935 --> 00:19:49,849
<i>to talk about the possibility
of what this computer could be.</i>

289
00:19:49,980 --> 00:19:53,815
And I think the key is not just
talking about the product,

290
00:19:53,943 --> 00:19:59,029
but giving you an idea
of what is possible using this product

291
00:19:59,156 --> 00:20:02,240
and what the next generation
is going to be like.

292
00:20:02,368 --> 00:20:06,203
So he gives people this feeling
of forward movement.

293
00:20:06,330 --> 00:20:09,118
- How many calculators do you own?
- Two, maybe.

294
00:20:09,291 --> 00:20:11,954
Right, and do you use
the automatic bank-telling machines?

295
00:20:12,086 --> 00:20:14,373
- Sure.
- Life is already seducing you

296
00:20:14,630 --> 00:20:17,748
into learning this stuff.
It's not going to happen at once,

297
00:20:17,883 --> 00:20:21,297
and it's certainly not
a <i>1984-ish</i> vision at all.

298
00:20:21,470 --> 00:20:24,178
It's just going to be very gradual
and very human

299
00:20:24,306 --> 00:20:26,798
and will seduce you
into learning how to use it.

300
00:20:28,978 --> 00:20:31,971
<i>Transitioning from a hobby
to a personal computer,</i>

301
00:20:32,106 --> 00:20:34,769
<i>that whole idea was driven by Steve.</i>

302
00:20:34,900 --> 00:20:37,108
He was trying to say
we need to differentiate ourselves

303
00:20:37,236 --> 00:20:38,898
and really move out
of this hobbyist realm.

304
00:20:39,029 --> 00:20:41,897
<i>It ended up
coming out of the room saying,</i>

305
00:20:42,032 --> 00:20:44,820
<i>"We're going to call ourselves
the personal computer."</i>

306
00:20:44,952 --> 00:20:46,568
<i>Industry experts say</i>

307
00:20:46,704 --> 00:20:49,822
<i>we're no longer on the verge
of the personal computer revolution.</i>

308
00:20:49,999 --> 00:20:51,535
<i>We're right in the midst of it,
thank you.</i>

309
00:20:51,667 --> 00:20:52,874
And it's gathering steam

310
00:20:53,002 --> 00:20:56,245
with more and more people
jumping aboard every day.

311
00:20:56,380 --> 00:21:00,044
I use my computer right now
for mostly word processing.

312
00:21:00,176 --> 00:21:03,886
I use it for solar evaluation programs.

313
00:21:04,013 --> 00:21:06,130
We put our entire accounting system
on it.

314
00:21:06,265 --> 00:21:08,052
The wife can use it to store recipes.

315
00:21:08,184 --> 00:21:09,595
To balance my checkbook for me.

316
00:21:09,769 --> 00:21:11,385
We do the computer club's bulletin.

317
00:21:11,562 --> 00:21:13,144
- Playing games.
- Shopping by mail.

318
00:21:13,272 --> 00:21:15,559
- Budgeting.
- Bowling-league type scores.

319
00:21:15,691 --> 00:21:18,149
- Electronic mail.
- A guy can be creative on it.

320
00:21:18,277 --> 00:21:20,519
I mean, he can use it
for whatever he can dream up.

321
00:21:20,654 --> 00:21:22,611
This is a 21st-century bicycle

322
00:21:22,740 --> 00:21:26,609
that amplifies a certain intellectual
ability that man has.

323
00:21:26,744 --> 00:21:29,578
The effects that it's going to
have on society

324
00:21:29,705 --> 00:21:31,287
are actually going to far outstrip

325
00:21:31,415 --> 00:21:34,032
even those that the petrochemical
revolution has had.

326
00:21:34,168 --> 00:21:35,168
<i>Time</i> magazine, I think,

327
00:21:35,294 --> 00:21:39,664
said single-handedly he created
the industry because he was relentless.

328
00:21:41,133 --> 00:21:44,592
<i>The powers that be
of "Time" magazine</i>

329
00:21:44,720 --> 00:21:50,182
decided that they would make
the Man of the Year that particular year

330
00:21:50,309 --> 00:21:52,551
the Computer of the Year.

331
00:21:52,686 --> 00:21:56,054
<i>I was transferred to the bureau
in San Francisco.</i>

332
00:21:56,190 --> 00:21:59,354
And gradually I began to cotton on
to the fact

333
00:21:59,485 --> 00:22:04,025
that there were a lot of stories
in this part of California

334
00:22:04,156 --> 00:22:08,196
between San Jose
and San Francisco

335
00:22:08,327 --> 00:22:09,943
about these odd, little companies

336
00:22:10,079 --> 00:22:13,072
that people on the East Coast
at that point

337
00:22:13,207 --> 00:22:16,666
hadn't heard about
and really didn't care about.

338
00:22:16,794 --> 00:22:18,877
<i>And then I got very interested in Apple</i>

339
00:22:19,004 --> 00:22:23,715
<i>and Steve was,
of the early characters in the company,</i>

340
00:22:23,926 --> 00:22:28,967
the most articulate and the most
interesting and the oddest.

341
00:22:29,098 --> 00:22:33,012
<i>Steven Jobs helped build
the first Apple computer in his garage.</i>

342
00:22:33,143 --> 00:22:36,181
<i>He is now 26 years old
and is chairman of the board.</i>

343
00:22:37,314 --> 00:22:38,725
<i>There was some debate</i>

344
00:22:38,858 --> 00:22:40,975
<i>over whether or not
they should use the name "Apple."</i>

345
00:22:41,110 --> 00:22:43,944
<i>You know, the whole model
of the computer industry</i>

346
00:22:44,071 --> 00:22:45,733
and the computer business was IBM.

347
00:22:45,865 --> 00:22:50,656
<i>Another business service of
tomorrow made possible today by IBM.</i>

348
00:22:50,786 --> 00:22:53,403
IBM was an anonymous organization.

349
00:22:53,539 --> 00:22:56,703
No one knew who the president was.
They probably had no idea.

350
00:22:56,834 --> 00:23:02,000
<i>The IBM logo looked like it was
carved out of Roman marble, you know?</i>

351
00:23:02,131 --> 00:23:04,839
It was just
this monolithic kind of thing.

352
00:23:04,967 --> 00:23:07,835
<i>And we took just the opposite,
which was,</i>

353
00:23:07,970 --> 00:23:11,259
<i>"Let's make Steve very high profile.
Let's tell our story."</i>

354
00:23:11,390 --> 00:23:14,224
<i>Working in this garage,
Jobs and a high-school classmate</i>

355
00:23:14,351 --> 00:23:16,684
<i>quit their positions
at large electronic companies,</i>

356
00:23:16,812 --> 00:23:21,432
<i>and using tiny silicon chips,
built this small computer board.</i>

357
00:23:26,780 --> 00:23:31,400
<i>Funny, the garage story was
less of a feature in those early days.</i>

358
00:23:31,577 --> 00:23:34,115
<i>It later on became more of a look back</i>

359
00:23:34,246 --> 00:23:39,037
<i>when people started doing stories
on the background, and so forth.</i>

360
00:23:39,168 --> 00:23:45,165
You know, I told Steve this,
and most of my clients in fact,

361
00:23:45,299 --> 00:23:49,168
there's a song in <i>Fiddler on the Roof</i>
that Tevye sings.

362
00:23:49,303 --> 00:23:53,673
He says, "If I were a rich man."
And he said, "I'd sit in the temple,

363
00:23:53,807 --> 00:23:56,891
and I'd lecture to the wise men
all day long,

364
00:23:57,019 --> 00:23:58,976
"and it wouldn't matter
if you're right or wrong."

365
00:23:59,104 --> 00:24:00,766
"When you're rich,
they think you know."

366
00:24:00,898 --> 00:24:02,514
So, in a technology business,

367
00:24:02,691 --> 00:24:06,526
you have to show that you are successful
in order to have a platform.

368
00:24:06,695 --> 00:24:09,233
<i>It led to
a quarter-billion-dollar business</i>

369
00:24:09,365 --> 00:24:13,325
<i>and the most popular typewriter-sized
computer on the market today.</i>

370
00:24:13,452 --> 00:24:16,240
Steve Jobs,
I realize this is your baby,

371
00:24:16,413 --> 00:24:17,949
and you've made a career out of it,

372
00:24:18,082 --> 00:24:20,540
but you're also
something of a philosopher.

373
00:24:20,709 --> 00:24:24,794
Do you see the inherent possibility
of bad coming out of all of this?

374
00:24:24,922 --> 00:24:27,255
Well, I think one of the things
you really have to look at

375
00:24:27,383 --> 00:24:30,091
is you have to go watch
some kids using these things.

376
00:24:30,219 --> 00:24:33,383
<i>And what you find is far
from something quite harmful.</i>

377
00:24:33,514 --> 00:24:35,005
<i>In effect, what you see</i>

378
00:24:35,182 --> 00:24:38,971
<i>is an instantaneous reflection
of a part of themselves,</i>

379
00:24:39,103 --> 00:24:41,561
the creative part of themselves
being expressed.

380
00:24:49,530 --> 00:24:51,988
<i>He was going for a computer</i>

381
00:24:52,116 --> 00:24:56,235
<i>that really felt like
an extension of the self.</i>

382
00:24:56,370 --> 00:25:00,284
That's what people wanted, and I think
he sensed that. He knew that.

383
00:25:01,417 --> 00:25:05,832
<i>My first book on the computer culture
was called "The Second Self."</i>

384
00:25:05,963 --> 00:25:07,920
<i>The key quote
that gave me the title was,</i>

385
00:25:08,048 --> 00:25:10,631
"When you think of a computer,"

386
00:25:10,801 --> 00:25:14,841
you put a little piece of your mind
into the computer's mind,

387
00:25:14,972 --> 00:25:17,259
"and you come to think
of yourself differently."

388
00:25:17,391 --> 00:25:23,012
Our whole company,
our whole philosophical base,

389
00:25:23,188 --> 00:25:27,273
is founded on one principle.
And that one principle

390
00:25:27,401 --> 00:25:32,271
is that there's something very special
and very historically different

391
00:25:32,406 --> 00:25:36,867
that takes place when you have
one computer and one person.

392
00:25:38,370 --> 00:25:40,703
<i>Did you have an opportunity
to meet Jobs?</i>

393
00:25:40,914 --> 00:25:43,156
<i>Yes,
I met him on several occasions.</i>

394
00:25:43,292 --> 00:25:45,284
And did you sense
from talking to him

395
00:25:45,419 --> 00:25:47,502
that he really did understand
what he was doing?

396
00:25:47,629 --> 00:25:49,791
I think he understood what he was doing.

397
00:25:51,008 --> 00:25:54,297
<i>He knew
he had created something intimate</i>

398
00:25:54,511 --> 00:25:57,504
<i>and that could be sold
as something intimate.</i>

399
00:25:57,639 --> 00:26:00,222
And it would be you.
I mean, it would be for you.

400
00:26:00,350 --> 00:26:04,469
It wasn't just for you. It was you.

401
00:26:10,486 --> 00:26:12,728
Can you just show me
the front of it?

402
00:26:12,905 --> 00:26:15,693
That's the part
that most people would recognize.

403
00:26:15,824 --> 00:26:19,568
This is a piece that everybody
remembers from the ads,

404
00:26:19,703 --> 00:26:23,322
from the <i>Time</i> magazine cover
with Steve holding it in his lap.

405
00:26:26,168 --> 00:26:29,411
And this is the famous beige that
we're never going to have any more of.

406
00:26:29,546 --> 00:26:31,208
He hated this even at this time,

407
00:26:31,340 --> 00:26:34,708
but we were kind of stuck with it
by the time we got there.

408
00:26:37,638 --> 00:26:40,176
It was a fun little machine.

409
00:26:44,603 --> 00:26:48,187
<i>He called me just out of the blue.
I was working at Xerox.</i>

410
00:26:49,358 --> 00:26:52,317
And I picked up the phone,
and it was Steve Jobs.

411
00:26:52,444 --> 00:26:55,937
And he said, "I hear you're a good guy",

412
00:26:56,073 --> 00:26:59,487
but everything you've done so far
is crap. Come work for me."

413
00:27:00,869 --> 00:27:05,113
<i>I told my wife at the time.
I said, "Well, what could happen?"</i>

414
00:27:05,249 --> 00:27:06,911
<i>"How bad could this be?"</i>

415
00:27:09,128 --> 00:27:11,370
I didn't realize how bad it could be.

416
00:27:15,092 --> 00:27:17,254
<i>First trip Steve ever made to Japan</i>

417
00:27:17,386 --> 00:27:20,424
<i>was to see what we could do about
getting a disc drive for the machine.</i>

418
00:27:20,556 --> 00:27:25,517
<i>And we saw the Sony disc facility
in Atsugi, Japan.</i>

419
00:27:25,644 --> 00:27:30,810
He had a lot of affection for Sony
because the Walkman was a machine

420
00:27:30,983 --> 00:27:33,020
that he just thought
was the bee's knees.

421
00:27:33,152 --> 00:27:36,065
♪ You really feel the music
with a Sony Walkman

422
00:27:36,196 --> 00:27:39,564
<i>The Sony Walkman is
a tiny stereo cassette player</i>

423
00:27:39,741 --> 00:27:42,154
<i>with truly incredible sound.</i>

424
00:27:42,286 --> 00:27:44,744
<i>♪ You really feel the music
You really feel it</i>

425
00:27:44,955 --> 00:27:47,368
I think it was the first product
in human history

426
00:27:47,499 --> 00:27:50,742
that went over a billion units.
That he liked.

427
00:27:51,795 --> 00:27:54,333
One of things that Steve thought
was important,

428
00:27:54,464 --> 00:27:56,126
and Jerry Manock facilitated it,

429
00:27:56,258 --> 00:27:58,671
was this is
where all the signatures are.

430
00:27:58,802 --> 00:28:02,295
And they're all the people,
the original group,

431
00:28:02,431 --> 00:28:08,974
that actually signed the machine.
There's Steve Jobs right in the middle.

432
00:28:10,105 --> 00:28:11,937
My name is over here.

433
00:28:12,107 --> 00:28:13,598
<i>Why did you do that?</i>

434
00:28:13,734 --> 00:28:17,569
Because the people that worked
on it consider themselves,

435
00:28:17,696 --> 00:28:20,154
and I certainly consider them, artists.

436
00:28:20,282 --> 00:28:22,649
These are the people that
under different circumstances

437
00:28:22,784 --> 00:28:26,994
<i>would be painters and poets, but,
because of the time that we live in,</i>

438
00:28:27,122 --> 00:28:29,239
<i>this new medium has appeared</i>

439
00:28:29,374 --> 00:28:32,538
<i>in which to express oneself
to one's fellow species.</i>

440
00:28:32,669 --> 00:28:36,037
And that's a medium of computing.

441
00:28:41,595 --> 00:28:45,214
<i>We would sit
in the temples in Kyoto,</i>

442
00:28:45,349 --> 00:28:49,719
<i>just taking off our shoes at the door
and sitting.</i>

443
00:29:03,659 --> 00:29:07,323
<i>Did he take from that any
kind of aesthetic vision, do you think?</i>

444
00:29:07,454 --> 00:29:11,573
<i>I think certainly. A simplicity.</i>

445
00:29:13,085 --> 00:29:16,044
Just feeling that inner calm

446
00:29:16,171 --> 00:29:20,290
that's so available
at some places in Japan.

447
00:29:22,386 --> 00:29:25,925
<i>He was a very much a person
who was comfortable in silence.</i>

448
00:29:36,066 --> 00:29:40,777
Steve ruled by a kind of a chaos.
