499
00:32:56,850 --> 00:32:59,012
<i>I think if you talk to a lot of
people on the Mac team,</i>

500
00:32:59,144 --> 00:33:05,141
they will tell you it was the hardest
they've ever worked in their life.

501
00:33:05,317 --> 00:33:07,024
Some of them will tell you
it was, you know,

502
00:33:07,277 --> 00:33:08,984
the happiest they've ever been
in their life,

503
00:33:09,112 --> 00:33:11,024
but I think all of them will tell you

504
00:33:11,156 --> 00:33:14,490
that it is certainly one of the most
intense and cherished experiences

505
00:33:14,618 --> 00:33:15,984
they will ever have in their life.

506
00:33:16,119 --> 00:33:18,953
- Mm-hmm. Yeah, they did.
- So...

507
00:33:21,750 --> 00:33:23,742
You know...

508
00:33:25,420 --> 00:33:29,960
Some of those things are
not sustainable for some people.

509
00:33:35,764 --> 00:33:38,347
<i>I ended up
changing my entire life.</i>

510
00:33:38,558 --> 00:33:40,766
I lost my wife in that process.

511
00:33:40,894 --> 00:33:44,558
I lost my children in that process.
I lost...

512
00:33:44,731 --> 00:33:48,441
The whole structure of my life
was just changed forever

513
00:33:48,568 --> 00:33:52,562
by going and working on the Mac.

514
00:33:52,697 --> 00:33:54,780
Because the work
became so intense?

515
00:33:54,908 --> 00:33:56,365
The work was intense.

516
00:33:56,493 --> 00:33:58,530
The commitment needed to do it
was intense.

517
00:33:58,662 --> 00:34:01,655
<i>I would go into work
on a Tuesday morning</i>

518
00:34:01,790 --> 00:34:03,656
<i>and half the people would hate me,</i>

519
00:34:03,792 --> 00:34:05,408
<i>and I'd come back on Wednesday morning,</i>

520
00:34:05,585 --> 00:34:08,168
<i>and half the people would hate me,
but it was the other half.</i>

521
00:34:08,338 --> 00:34:10,751
<i>There were an awful lot
of prima donnas in that outfit,</i>

522
00:34:10,882 --> 00:34:13,590
<i>so I was always in conflict.</i>

523
00:34:16,805 --> 00:34:20,515
Here's the piece you wrote.
You want to read it?

524
00:34:21,851 --> 00:34:26,391
"Steve's passing did come
as a bit of a shock for me."

525
00:34:26,523 --> 00:34:31,393
"For a bit more than three years,
1982 to 1985,

526
00:34:31,528 --> 00:34:34,236
we were together a lot of the time."

527
00:34:34,406 --> 00:34:38,491
"We made a dozen trips to Japan
together. We were close."

528
00:34:38,618 --> 00:34:41,656
"After that,
I only saw him a few times."

529
00:34:41,788 --> 00:34:44,155
"I haven't seen him in many years."

530
00:34:44,332 --> 00:34:48,667
"He was an extraordinary person in many
ways and quite normal in others."

531
00:34:48,795 --> 00:34:52,254
<i>"The outpouring of feelings
from people all over the world</i>

532
00:34:52,465 --> 00:34:57,130
<i>was a bit of a surprise to me at first,
and then it seemed natural."</i>

533
00:34:57,262 --> 00:35:00,050
<i>"He was for them
a combination of James Dean,</i>

534
00:35:00,181 --> 00:35:04,050
<i>Princess Diana and John Lennon
and maybe Santa Claus."</i>

535
00:35:04,185 --> 00:35:07,849
"What is in that bag of goodies?"

536
00:35:08,773 --> 00:35:12,642
<i>"The iPod, the iPhone
and the iPad are so personal."</i>

537
00:35:12,777 --> 00:35:17,772
<i>"They are warm in your hand.
They sing to you when you're alone."</i>

538
00:35:17,907 --> 00:35:19,364
<i>"They are caressed."</i>

539
00:35:21,870 --> 00:35:23,156
"In those three years together,

540
00:35:23,288 --> 00:35:26,247
I packed in a decade or two
of experience."

541
00:35:26,416 --> 00:35:31,787
"Steve packed in a couple of centuries
in his 56 years."

542
00:35:31,921 --> 00:35:36,461
"He did everything he wanted,
and all on his own terms."

543
00:35:36,593 --> 00:35:39,461
"It was a life well and fully lived,

544
00:35:39,596 --> 00:35:43,055
even if it was a bit expensive
for those of us who were close."

545
00:35:47,604 --> 00:35:50,062
You do have friends, you know?

546
00:35:50,190 --> 00:35:53,308
Even if they're bizarre people.

547
00:35:55,612 --> 00:35:58,480
Yes. He is.
He's one of those mythic characters.

548
00:35:58,615 --> 00:36:05,658
Yeah, and they're not that much fun
on the ground most of the time,

549
00:36:05,789 --> 00:36:09,328
but there are those moments
when suddenly...

550
00:36:11,086 --> 00:36:13,703
They're the only person
who could've ever done it.

551
00:36:13,922 --> 00:36:15,288
Right.

552
00:36:15,465 --> 00:36:19,084
- Yeah, and they change us.
- Right.

553
00:36:32,440 --> 00:36:35,774
<i>Without death,
there would be very little progress.</i>

554
00:36:35,902 --> 00:36:39,316
<i>I'm sure that life evolved
without death at first</i>

555
00:36:39,489 --> 00:36:44,826
<i>and found that without death,
life didn't work very well.</i>

556
00:36:44,953 --> 00:36:48,321
<i>Because it didn't make room
for the young</i>

557
00:36:48,498 --> 00:36:52,913
<i>who didn't know how the world was,
you know, 50 years ago,</i>

558
00:36:53,044 --> 00:36:56,754
<i>but who saw it as it is today
without any preconceptions</i>

559
00:36:56,881 --> 00:36:59,248
<i>and dreamed how it could be
based on that.</i>

560
00:37:04,097 --> 00:37:07,181
<i>The minute that you understand
that you can poke life,</i>

561
00:37:07,308 --> 00:37:09,140
<i>you can change it, you can mold it,</i>

562
00:37:09,269 --> 00:37:11,886
<i>you'll want to change life
and make it better</i>

563
00:37:12,021 --> 00:37:14,013
<i>cos it's kind of messed up
in a lot of ways.</i>

564
00:37:15,150 --> 00:37:18,234
<i>Once you learn that,
you'll never be the same again.</i>

565
00:37:23,783 --> 00:37:24,990
<i>Just be here.</i>

566
00:37:25,994 --> 00:37:30,955
<i>Don't judge, don't try,
don't stop, don't start. Just be here.</i>

567
00:37:31,082 --> 00:37:32,698
<i>It's all just enough.</i>

568
00:37:36,629 --> 00:37:38,996
<i>It's enough to know that I love you.</i>

569
00:37:42,677 --> 00:37:47,297
<i>Steve and I met two weeks into
our freshman year at Reed College.</i>

570
00:37:47,432 --> 00:37:51,642
<i>We had both happened to buy
"Be Here Now."</i>

571
00:37:51,811 --> 00:37:55,725
And it was such an unusual book.
I just wanted...

572
00:37:55,857 --> 00:37:58,975
I was carrying it around
and wanted somebody to talk to about it,

573
00:37:59,110 --> 00:38:02,353
and Steve was the one person
who also had read it.

574
00:38:09,829 --> 00:38:11,286
<i>When we went to India,</i>

575
00:38:11,414 --> 00:38:15,909
<i>we were looking for
remarkable experiences.</i>

576
00:38:16,044 --> 00:38:19,583
<i>We didn't have a guru.
We didn't have a particular school.</i>

577
00:38:19,714 --> 00:38:22,832
<i>And so we traveled around
for four months.</i>

578
00:38:22,967 --> 00:38:29,931
<i>Had some interesting experiences.
No major enlightenment experiences.</i>

579
00:38:30,058 --> 00:38:32,425
Steve's quote later was,

580
00:38:32,602 --> 00:38:35,094
"We had figured out that
we weren't going to meet somebody

581
00:38:35,230 --> 00:38:37,438
who was going to make us enlightened."

582
00:38:40,193 --> 00:38:42,401
<i>If you think about Hindu spirituality,</i>

583
00:38:42,570 --> 00:38:46,439
<i>you think of Mother Teresa
feeding the poor.</i>

584
00:38:46,616 --> 00:38:49,950
<i>That's not really the path
that Steve took.</i>

585
00:38:50,078 --> 00:38:52,741
Those weren't Steve's values.

586
00:38:55,708 --> 00:38:57,825
<i>It was the next year,
after India,</i>

587
00:38:57,961 --> 00:39:02,001
<i>when he connected
with the Zen Center in Los Altos.</i>

588
00:39:02,131 --> 00:39:08,594
<i>Zen is about clarity,
simplicity, cleanliness.</i>

589
00:39:09,472 --> 00:39:15,264
<i>Ending the duality of your ego
and simplifying your life.</i>

590
00:39:15,395 --> 00:39:18,479
<i>And that really appealed to Steve.</i>

591
00:39:18,648 --> 00:39:23,313
It's based on taking off
and creating something for yourself.

592
00:39:23,444 --> 00:39:27,438
You know, giving life to your own life
in whatever way you wish to do it.

593
00:39:28,908 --> 00:39:30,991
<i>At the time
he was starting Apple,</i>

594
00:39:31,119 --> 00:39:34,908
<i>Steve was very actively looking
for a mentor.</i>

595
00:39:39,419 --> 00:39:43,208
<i>Kobun Chino would
become Jobs's spiritual advisor.</i>

596
00:39:43,381 --> 00:39:47,716
<i>Kobun encouraged Jobs
not to retreat into a monastery,</i>

597
00:39:47,844 --> 00:39:51,554
<i>but instead to find Zen
in his life and work.</i>

598
00:39:51,764 --> 00:39:54,848
<i>But they would argue
over the path to enlightenment.</i>

599
00:40:08,114 --> 00:40:14,907
Steve always says, "Make me monk.
