1084
01:13:47,381 --> 01:13:50,044
Was that a heartfelt thing for Steve?

1085
01:13:50,176 --> 01:13:52,543
I believe it was
a heartfelt thing for Steve.

1086
01:13:52,720 --> 01:13:55,303
I think that he did want to make
the world a better place.

1087
01:13:55,514 --> 01:14:00,054
I think that he felt
by delivering great products

1088
01:14:00,186 --> 01:14:03,805
that were easy to use and beautiful,

1089
01:14:03,940 --> 01:14:06,398
that it would
make people's lives better.

1090
01:14:09,779 --> 01:14:11,361
<i>Is that enough?</i>

1091
01:14:11,489 --> 01:14:15,108
<i>Is making and selling products,
even if they're good,</i>

1092
01:14:15,242 --> 01:14:18,861
<i>even if they're the best, enough
to make the world a better place?</i>

1093
01:14:20,790 --> 01:14:22,201
<i>Apple's a business.</i>

1094
01:14:22,333 --> 01:14:25,497
And we've somehow attached
this emotion to a business,

1095
01:14:25,711 --> 01:14:29,330
which is just there to make money
for its shareholders, right?

1096
01:14:29,465 --> 01:14:30,922
That's all it is. Nothing more.

1097
01:14:31,050 --> 01:14:32,882
<i>You know, creating that association</i>

1098
01:14:33,094 --> 01:14:36,508
<i>was probably one of Steve's
greatest accomplishments.</i>

1099
01:14:36,639 --> 01:14:39,006
- It's queued up to play.
- Awesome.

1100
01:14:41,936 --> 01:14:45,771
I remember at this point, when the music
plays in the beginning,

1101
01:14:45,898 --> 01:14:47,560
there's just this energy, right?

1102
01:14:47,733 --> 01:14:52,524
You have on the one side
this huge bank of photographers,

1103
01:14:52,655 --> 01:14:56,569
<i>and I remember
looking at all these guys</i>

1104
01:14:56,742 --> 01:14:59,234
with their cameras trained on Steve,
thinking,

1105
01:14:59,370 --> 01:15:02,113
"You guys have no idea
what's about to happen."

1106
01:15:02,248 --> 01:15:03,955
And to be fair, neither did we.

1107
01:15:07,253 --> 01:15:09,586
Thank you for coming.

1108
01:15:09,755 --> 01:15:11,917
We're going to make some history
together today.

1109
01:15:13,050 --> 01:15:14,757
<i>Any time you see an Apple event,</i>

1110
01:15:14,885 --> 01:15:18,925
know that there's a team of people
in the audience who are just sick.

1111
01:15:22,852 --> 01:15:26,391
We are calling it "iPhone."

1112
01:15:28,190 --> 01:15:34,812
Today... Today,
Apple is going to reinvent the phone.

1113
01:15:34,947 --> 01:15:38,691
And so, rather than talk about this
some more, let me show it to you.

1114
01:15:38,868 --> 01:15:42,908
<i>So, if you're giving a demo,
and you deviate off the script,</i>

1115
01:15:43,039 --> 01:15:44,496
<i>well, lots of bad things
can go wrong.</i>

1116
01:15:44,623 --> 01:15:48,367
When Steve comes up with,
"Here's what I want to show,"

1117
01:15:48,502 --> 01:15:49,993
everything is dissected.

1118
01:15:50,171 --> 01:15:51,503
The message that he's trying to say

1119
01:15:51,630 --> 01:15:53,587
is then dissected
into very specific actions.

1120
01:15:53,716 --> 01:15:57,710
And let me go ahead and get
that picture within picture up.

1121
01:15:57,887 --> 01:16:01,051
I'm going to go ahead and just push
the "sleep wake" button.

1122
01:16:01,182 --> 01:16:03,094
There we go, right there.

1123
01:16:03,225 --> 01:16:06,559
And to unlock the phone, I just take
my finger and slide it across.

1124
01:16:06,687 --> 01:16:09,145
All right, you want to see that again?

1125
01:16:10,816 --> 01:16:14,025
<i>So, he's got, you know,
several discrete parts of the demo.</i>

1126
01:16:14,236 --> 01:16:20,028
We had a flask of Scotch with us,
and after every little part,

1127
01:16:20,159 --> 01:16:23,994
the person who was responsible for
that portion, you know, took a hit.

1128
01:16:24,121 --> 01:16:26,488
I want to make a call to Jony Ive.

1129
01:16:26,707 --> 01:16:27,914
I can just push here,

1130
01:16:28,042 --> 01:16:30,580
and I see Jony Ive's contacts
with all his information.

1131
01:16:30,711 --> 01:16:33,419
The Jony Ive call, oh, my God.

1132
01:16:33,547 --> 01:16:36,460
<i>There's all sorts of ways that
this could have gone sideways.</i>

1133
01:16:36,592 --> 01:16:39,926
- Hey, Jony, how you doing?
<i>- I'm good. How you doing?</i>

1134
01:16:40,054 --> 01:16:44,640
Well, it's been two-and-a-half years,
and I can't tell you how thrilled I am

1135
01:16:44,767 --> 01:16:47,555
to make the first public phone call
with iPhone.

1136
01:16:50,523 --> 01:16:51,934
He goes to the music.

1137
01:16:52,066 --> 01:16:54,274
Let's go into Dylan here.

1138
01:16:54,401 --> 01:16:56,313
Let's play <i>Like a Rolling Stone.</i>

1139
01:16:58,989 --> 01:17:00,605
He gets the web browser up there.

1140
01:17:00,741 --> 01:17:04,234
I want to show you Safari
running on a mobile device.

1141
01:17:04,370 --> 01:17:06,532
So, let's go to the web. Boom.

1142
01:17:06,664 --> 01:17:08,326
Unbelievable.

1143
01:17:08,457 --> 01:17:11,120
And then at the end,
he has that moment

1144
01:17:11,252 --> 01:17:13,289
where he swizzles it all together.

1145
01:17:13,420 --> 01:17:17,004
<i>At the end, where he orders thousands
of lattes from some, you know,</i>

1146
01:17:17,133 --> 01:17:19,420
<i>poor woman at a Starbucks
down the road.</i>

1147
01:17:19,552 --> 01:17:21,965
<i>Good morning. This is Starbucks
and how can I help you?</i>

1148
01:17:22,096 --> 01:17:24,554
Yes, I'd liked to order
4,000 lattes to go, please.

1149
01:17:24,682 --> 01:17:26,093
No, just kidding.

1150
01:17:26,225 --> 01:17:29,639
Wrong number. Thank you. Bye-bye.

1151
01:17:29,770 --> 01:17:31,477
OK.

1152
01:17:38,737 --> 01:17:41,275
As soon as the demo was over,
we left.

1153
01:17:41,407 --> 01:17:46,243
And we just turned San Francisco
into a... It was a shit show.

1154
01:17:53,586 --> 01:17:55,498
That was a night to remember.

1155
01:17:56,672 --> 01:18:00,211
<i>Man, you just had this release
of years of anxiety.</i>

1156
01:18:00,342 --> 01:18:03,585
And then we got up tomorrow,
the next day, and did it all over again.

1157
01:18:03,721 --> 01:18:05,587
And we had to finish the product
at this point.

1158
01:18:05,764 --> 01:18:08,302
And that was tough,
especially with a raging hangover,

1159
01:18:08,434 --> 01:18:10,346
but it was a lot of fun.

1160
01:18:10,477 --> 01:18:14,312
The biggest thing he made was
the iPhone, definitely.

1161
01:18:14,440 --> 01:18:15,976
He made the iPhone,

1162
01:18:16,150 --> 01:18:19,769
which shocked the world
with its touch screen and stuff.

1163
01:18:24,450 --> 01:18:28,820
So, what are we down to?
13 minutes and...

1164
01:18:28,996 --> 01:18:30,407
Whoo-hoo!

1165
01:18:30,539 --> 01:18:33,077
- It's go time!
- Oh, yeah.

1166
01:18:42,426 --> 01:18:46,466
- Oh, yeah. Swipe to unlock.
- Sweet!

1167
01:18:50,184 --> 01:18:53,677
<i>♪ All my life</i>

1168
01:18:53,812 --> 01:18:56,054
<i>♪ Is changing every day</i>

1169
01:18:56,190 --> 01:18:57,681
There she is.

1170
01:18:57,900 --> 01:19:00,062
<i>♪ In every possible way</i>

1171
01:19:00,194 --> 01:19:03,687
iPhone's been shipping
for exactly 200 days today.

1172
01:19:03,822 --> 01:19:07,031
And I'm extraordinarily pleased
to report

1173
01:19:07,159 --> 01:19:10,493
that we have sold
four million iPhones to date.

1174
01:19:12,456 --> 01:19:15,494
<i>♪ Never quite as it seems</i>

1175
01:19:15,626 --> 01:19:18,994
<i>♪ And then I open up and see</i>

1176
01:19:19,129 --> 01:19:23,544
<i>♪ The person falling here is me</i>

1177
01:19:23,676 --> 01:19:27,636
Today we're introducing
the iPhone 3G.

1178
01:19:33,644 --> 01:19:39,185
In a little over two years,
we have sold 30 million iPhones.

1179
01:19:47,533 --> 01:19:50,241
And with a swipe,
you have changed your life.

1180
01:19:50,369 --> 01:19:52,201
Yes!

1181
01:20:04,508 --> 01:20:08,422
- How may I help you?
- IPhone 4. Where is the iPhone 4?

1182
01:20:08,554 --> 01:20:12,389
Oh, I'm very sorry,
but we are currently sold out.

1183
01:20:12,516 --> 01:20:16,681
However, we did finally get
some more HTC Evos in.

1184
01:20:16,812 --> 01:20:19,771
What? What is that?
Is it an iPhone?

1185
01:20:19,898 --> 01:20:22,686
No, it is that 4G phone on Sprint.

1186
01:20:22,818 --> 01:20:25,231
If it's not an iPhone,
why would I want it?

1187
01:20:25,362 --> 01:20:28,355
Well, it's similar to an iPhone,
but has a bigger screen.

1188
01:20:28,490 --> 01:20:29,651
I don't care.

1189
01:20:29,783 --> 01:20:32,446
The internet speeds
are around three times faster.

1190
01:20:32,578 --> 01:20:35,195
- I don't care.
- It fucking prints money.

1191
01:20:35,331 --> 01:20:38,244
- I don't care.
- It can grant up to three wishes.

1192
01:20:38,375 --> 01:20:40,833
Even if one of those wishes
is for an iPhone.

1193
01:20:40,961 --> 01:20:43,453
- I don't care about any of that.
- OK, fine.

1194
01:20:43,589 --> 01:20:46,457
Then what the hell entices you
about the iPhone 4,

1195
01:20:46,592 --> 01:20:48,549
if you don't mind me asking?

1196
01:20:48,677 --> 01:20:50,384
It is an iPhone.

1197
01:21:00,606 --> 01:21:05,192
<i>I remember the first set of
people I interviewed about the iPhone.</i>

1198
01:21:05,319 --> 01:21:07,902
<i>I've been interviewing people
about their computers</i>

1199
01:21:08,030 --> 01:21:09,987
<i>for, you know, decades.</i>

1200
01:21:10,157 --> 01:21:16,324
<i>I've never seen this kind of connection
before with an object.</i>

1201
01:21:18,290 --> 01:21:21,909
<i>In the beginning,
the impulse was to sit you down</i>

1202
01:21:22,044 --> 01:21:25,754
<i>and to show you everything
on their iPhone.</i>

1203
01:21:25,964 --> 01:21:29,548
<i>As time's gone on,
there's been less of that</i>

1204
01:21:29,676 --> 01:21:34,341
<i>and more of what I call
the "alone together phenomenon."</i>

1205
01:21:37,851 --> 01:21:42,016
It has turned out to be
an isolating technology.

1206
01:21:53,367 --> 01:21:55,404
<i>Did you ever see
that Wim Wenders film,</i>

1207
01:21:55,536 --> 01:21:56,697
<i>"Until the End of the World"?</i>

1208
01:21:56,829 --> 01:22:00,823
<i>Yes, I love that.
People fall in love with their dreams,</i>

1209
01:22:00,958 --> 01:22:04,622
<i>and they walk around
with hoods over their head</i>

1210
01:22:04,753 --> 01:22:09,043
<i>and screens in front of them,
fascinated by their dreams.</i>

1211
01:22:09,216 --> 01:22:13,335
<i>By the time I came to rescue
Claire, the only thing she cared about</i>

1212
01:22:13,470 --> 01:22:16,838
<i>was having fresh batteries
for her video monitor.</i>

1213
01:22:19,059 --> 01:22:20,721
<i>It's a little bit like that.</i>

1214
01:22:20,853 --> 01:22:24,938
<i>It's a dream machine,
and you become fascinated</i>

1215
01:22:25,065 --> 01:22:28,979
<i>by the world that you can find
on these screens.</i>

1216
01:22:30,362 --> 01:22:34,697
<i>And the face of that technology
was Steve Jobs.</i>

1217
01:22:55,971 --> 01:23:00,011
What would you say about
the responsibilities of power

1218
01:23:00,142 --> 01:23:03,476
once you've achieved
a certain level of success?

1219
01:23:03,604 --> 01:23:07,018
Power? What is that?

1220
01:23:13,864 --> 01:23:16,322
<i>♪ Your daddy, he's an outlaw</i>

1221
01:23:16,533 --> 01:23:18,900
<i>He found a loophole
where if you lease a car,</i>

1222
01:23:19,036 --> 01:23:22,825
you have a six-month grace period
to put license plates on.

1223
01:23:22,956 --> 01:23:28,543
And so he leased the same car
every six months,

1224
01:23:28,670 --> 01:23:30,832
to avoid putting license plates
at all.

1225
01:23:31,006 --> 01:23:32,668
<i>I think he told people</i>

1226
01:23:32,799 --> 01:23:37,385
that it's because he didn't
want people to identify him.

1227
01:23:37,513 --> 01:23:39,425
Well, there's nothing more identifiable

1228
01:23:39,556 --> 01:23:41,889
than a silver Mercedes
with no license plate.

1229
01:23:42,017 --> 01:23:44,634
I mean, it screams "Steve Jobs"
in the Valley.

1230
01:23:44,770 --> 01:23:48,559
Riding to work with Steve Jobs.

1231
01:23:48,690 --> 01:23:51,603
Riding to work
with the good ol' Stevie.

1232
01:23:53,946 --> 01:23:57,565
Oh, look at that,
he's in the carpool lane.

1233
01:23:57,699 --> 01:24:01,568
And it does give you a glimpse
of how he thought he was above the law.

1234
01:24:01,703 --> 01:24:06,323
<i>♪ He oversees his kingdom
Where no stranger does intrude</i>

1235
01:24:06,500 --> 01:24:09,334
<i>♪ His voice
It trembles as he calls out</i>

1236
01:24:09,461 --> 01:24:11,999
<i>♪ For another plate of food</i>

1237
01:24:12,130 --> 01:24:15,589
<i>♪ One more cup of coffee for the road</i>

1238
01:24:15,717 --> 01:24:19,427
<i>Jobs also made it a habit
to park his plateless Mercedes Benz</i>

1239
01:24:19,555 --> 01:24:22,468
<i>in handicap parking spots
around the Apple campus.</i>

1240
01:24:23,892 --> 01:24:26,384
<i>It even became something
of a pastime in the Valley,</i>

1241
01:24:26,520 --> 01:24:29,308
<i>to take a picture next to Steve's car.</i>

1242
01:24:30,607 --> 01:24:34,692
<i>♪ One more cup of coffee before I go</i>

1243
01:24:34,820 --> 01:24:37,312
<i>♪ To the valley below</i>

1244
01:24:41,618 --> 01:24:45,362
<i>He was a hero in the Valley
because he made buckets of money,</i>

1245
01:24:45,497 --> 01:24:46,908
<i>but unlike Bill Gates,</i>

1246
01:24:47,040 --> 01:24:50,829
<i>Jobs told people that giving away money
was a waste of time.</i>

1247
01:24:50,961 --> 01:24:56,923
<i>Under Jobs, Apple terminated
its philanthropic programs.</i>

1248
01:24:57,050 --> 01:25:00,168
<i>Jobs kept acting
as if Apple was a start-up,</i>

1249
01:25:00,345 --> 01:25:04,635
<i>but by 2010, it was one of the most
valuable companies in the world.</i>

1250
01:25:05,684 --> 01:25:09,223
<i>Among the rich and famous,
Jobs was a compelling character.</i>

1251
01:25:09,396 --> 01:25:14,733
<i>A counter-culture businessman.
But what were his values as a citizen?</i>

1252
01:25:14,860 --> 01:25:17,443
<i>Was he interested in power
to change the world</i>

1253
01:25:17,571 --> 01:25:20,814
<i>or the right to have power
without responsibility?</i>

1254
01:25:24,411 --> 01:25:27,119
<i>There was an experience
where actually a couple of people</i>

1255
01:25:27,247 --> 01:25:28,954
<i>were fighting over you,
were they not?</i>

1256
01:25:29,082 --> 01:25:31,995
- Oh, man. I went to Palm.
- Then a bunch of people went to Palm.

1257
01:25:32,127 --> 01:25:33,584
Yeah. Yeah.

1258
01:25:33,712 --> 01:25:36,375
- Was Steve pissed off?
- Oh, man. Yeah.

1259
01:25:36,506 --> 01:25:40,750
I gave my resignation.
It went up the chain, like you do.

1260
01:25:40,886 --> 01:25:45,256
And just sure as hell,
like 20 minutes later,

1261
01:25:45,432 --> 01:25:48,675
I get a call from Steve's admin,
"Steve wants to see you."

1262
01:25:49,895 --> 01:25:53,059
<i>He sits down. He just kind of sits
there, and he looks at me.</i>

1263
01:25:53,190 --> 01:25:56,604
And I start to kind of launch
into my little spiel that I had planned,

1264
01:25:56,735 --> 01:26:00,854
and he says, "You know
you fucked up Bluetooth, right?"

1265
01:26:00,989 --> 01:26:03,106
I just stopped. I'm like...

1266
01:26:03,325 --> 01:26:06,739
And then we go through
this half-hour mind fuck.

1267
01:26:06,870 --> 01:26:09,078
<i>It becomes very "Godfather" - esque.</i>

1268
01:26:09,206 --> 01:26:12,415
<i>You know, "You're part of my family,
and Apple's my family,</i>

1269
01:26:12,542 --> 01:26:14,249
<i>and you don't want to leave my family."</i>

1270
01:26:14,419 --> 01:26:18,333
And at the end, he says,
"If you choose to leave my family,"

1271
01:26:18,507 --> 01:26:23,172
should you decide to take so much
as one member of my family away from me,

1272
01:26:23,303 --> 01:26:25,420
"I will personally take you down."

1273
01:26:26,556 --> 01:26:28,593
<i>To keep his family together,</i>

1274
01:26:28,725 --> 01:26:33,561
<i>Jobs was willing to let Apple bend
or even break the law.</i>

1275
01:26:33,689 --> 01:26:36,853
<i>In 2011, a class-action lawsuit</i>

1276
01:26:36,983 --> 01:26:40,272
<i>filed by more than
64,000 Silicon Valley workers</i>

1277
01:26:40,445 --> 01:26:44,689
<i>revealed that Jobs, along with
the CEOs of Google, Intel and Adobe</i>

1278
01:26:44,825 --> 01:26:48,364
<i>had colluded not to recruit
each other's employees.</i>

1279
01:26:48,537 --> 01:26:51,655
If you're working there at Apple,
or wherever you're working,

1280
01:26:51,790 --> 01:26:54,749
you've got another company
that you might move to

1281
01:26:54,876 --> 01:26:57,789
and take your expertise with you
and earn more money at that company.

1282
01:26:57,921 --> 01:27:00,834
They won't accept your résumé.
They won't return your phone calls.

1283
01:27:00,966 --> 01:27:03,504
Right. Because they won't
let them poach each other.

1284
01:27:03,635 --> 01:27:06,048
- Correct.
- That's not a legitimate situation.

1285
01:27:06,179 --> 01:27:08,045
You know what some of
the strongest evidence was?

1286
01:27:08,181 --> 01:27:10,468
E-mails of the late, great Steve Jobs.

1287
01:27:10,600 --> 01:27:12,262
- Really?
- Tons of them, yes.

1288
01:27:17,733 --> 01:27:20,692
<i>Less than a month after
Google co-founder Sergey Brin</i>

1289
01:27:20,819 --> 01:27:22,856
<i>received this threat from Jobs,</i>

1290
01:27:22,988 --> 01:27:28,529
<i>Google circulated a "do not cold
call" list that included Apple.</i>

1291
01:27:28,660 --> 01:27:31,198
<i>Two years later, Google tried again,</i>

1292
01:27:31,329 --> 01:27:34,197
<i>and Jobs e-mailed Google CEO
Eric Schmidt</i>

1293
01:27:34,332 --> 01:27:36,745
<i>to remind him of their
gentlemen's agreement.</i>

1294
01:27:39,254 --> 01:27:41,587
<i>Schmidt placated Jobs by assuring him</i>

1295
01:27:41,715 --> 01:27:45,584
<i>that the culprit would be fired
within the hour.</i>

1296
01:27:45,719 --> 01:27:48,427
<i>When Jobs learned
that the woman had been canned,</i>

1297
01:27:48,680 --> 01:27:52,390
<i>he showed his pleasure
in two efficient keystrokes.</i>

1298
01:27:58,023 --> 01:28:01,266
Someone's going to come out
of the door. Do we want a shot of that?

1299
01:28:05,530 --> 01:28:08,022
Are you taking a picture
of the inside?

1300
01:28:08,158 --> 01:28:10,616
We're taking a picture
of the Apple logo on the door.

1301
01:28:10,744 --> 01:28:14,203
OK, we cannot have people
taking pictures.

1302
01:28:14,331 --> 01:28:16,072
<i>Tonight, a Wall Street scandal</i>

1303
01:28:16,208 --> 01:28:19,042
<i>has reached deep into
an iconic American company,</i>

1304
01:28:19,169 --> 01:28:20,705
<i>the Apple Corporation.</i>

1305
01:28:20,837 --> 01:28:23,295
It all centers on an alleged scheme

1306
01:28:23,423 --> 01:28:27,667
to under-report Apple's expenses
by $40 million,

1307
01:28:27,803 --> 01:28:29,544
including $20 million

1308
01:28:29,679 --> 01:28:33,218
that went straight to the company's
celebrity CEO Steve Jobs,

1309
01:28:33,391 --> 01:28:38,227
<i>in the form of what are known
as backdated options.</i>

1310
01:28:38,355 --> 01:28:42,895
I first met Steve Jobs shortly after
I became editor of <i>Fortune</i> magazine.

1311
01:28:43,944 --> 01:28:46,652
<i>"And I said," Listen, we'd love to have
a good relationship with Apple</i>

1312
01:28:46,780 --> 01:28:47,780
<i>and do stories about you."</i>

1313
01:28:47,906 --> 01:28:50,489
And he said, "Look,
this is how it's going to work."

1314
01:28:50,617 --> 01:28:52,779
"You know,
you want to do a story about us,

1315
01:28:52,911 --> 01:28:56,780
you call us up, propose it,
you know, we'll think about it."

1316
01:28:56,915 --> 01:28:59,783
"We'll basically
come up with the ideas with you,"

1317
01:28:59,918 --> 01:29:02,160
or come up with the ideas,
we'll call you,

1318
01:29:02,295 --> 01:29:06,960
"we'll figure out who the writer is going
to be on your staff to do the story."

1319
01:29:07,092 --> 01:29:11,211
And I said, "Well, you know, Steve,
that's not really how we do things."

1320
01:29:11,346 --> 01:29:13,429
And he goes, "That's how
you do things with Apple."

1321
01:29:14,432 --> 01:29:15,432
<i>So I say to myself,</i>

1322
01:29:15,517 --> 01:29:18,601
<i>"Why don't we do a story
about the stock options?"</i>

1323
01:29:18,728 --> 01:29:21,095
<i>"Because no one's
really figured it out."</i>

1324
01:29:21,231 --> 01:29:25,851
So, I decided to put one of our top
investigative reporters on the story,

1325
01:29:25,986 --> 01:29:26,986
Peter Elkind.

1326
01:29:27,112 --> 01:29:30,526
Steve Jobs had a very talented group
of key lieutenants around him.

1327
01:29:30,699 --> 01:29:34,989
<i>And he wanted give his people stock
option grants that were so big,</i>

1328
01:29:35,120 --> 01:29:37,328
<i>that they wouldn't even think about
going somewhere else</i>

1329
01:29:37,455 --> 01:29:39,367
<i>because the upside was so enormous.</i>

1330
01:29:39,499 --> 01:29:44,619
The key thing is if the stock goes up,

1331
01:29:44,754 --> 01:29:47,872
which we always hope it does,

1332
01:29:48,008 --> 01:29:53,299
then the golden handcuffs are
dramatically increased,

1333
01:29:53,430 --> 01:29:56,639
which is what I was hoping
would happen.

1334
01:29:57,517 --> 01:29:59,725
<i>To make those option deals
even sweeter,</i>

1335
01:29:59,853 --> 01:30:04,063
<i>companies would allow executives
to buy stock on dates in the past</i>

1336
01:30:04,190 --> 01:30:05,351
<i>when the price was low</i>

1337
01:30:05,483 --> 01:30:08,442
<i>so executives could make
millions in the blink of an eye.</i>

1338
01:30:08,570 --> 01:30:10,357
<i>This was called "backdating."</i>

1339
01:30:10,488 --> 01:30:12,320
<i>And it seemed like
the perfect solution,</i>

1340
01:30:12,532 --> 01:30:13,532
<i>except for one thing.</i>

1341
01:30:13,700 --> 01:30:16,943
<i>If not properly reported,
backdating is illegal.</i>

1342
01:30:17,078 --> 01:30:20,571
200 US public companies
are under investigation

1343
01:30:20,749 --> 01:30:24,914
over charges of backdated stock options
for their senior executives.

1344
01:30:26,296 --> 01:30:28,128
<i>Backdating was a dicey game,</i>

1345
01:30:28,256 --> 01:30:30,919
<i>and it landed several executives
in jail for fraud,</i>

1346
01:30:31,051 --> 01:30:34,544
<i>but it became a frequent practice
at Apple under Jobs.</i>

1347
01:30:34,721 --> 01:30:37,134
<i>Apple eventually conducted
an internal investigation</i>

1348
01:30:37,265 --> 01:30:38,551
<i>and found thousands of cases</i>

1349
01:30:38,725 --> 01:30:40,933
<i>where stock options had been
handled inappropriately.</i>

1350
01:30:41,061 --> 01:30:43,599
None of that had taken place
according to the company's own report

1351
01:30:43,855 --> 01:30:46,063
before Steve Jobs had returned there.

1352
01:30:46,191 --> 01:30:49,229
<i>A key advisor on many of
the troubled backdating schemes</i>

1353
01:30:49,361 --> 01:30:52,980
<i>was a powerful Silicon Valley attorney,
Larry Sonsini.</i>

1354
01:30:53,114 --> 01:30:55,197
<i>Larry Sonsini had kind of</i>

1355
01:30:55,325 --> 01:30:57,487
spread this dark art
in the world of Silicon Valley.

1356
01:30:57,619 --> 01:31:01,363
<i>He's the guy who whispered to the CEOs
of all the top tech companies,</i>

1357
01:31:01,539 --> 01:31:03,030
<i>"Here's how you can do this."</i>

1358
01:31:03,166 --> 01:31:05,909
<i>He was certainly very close
to Steve Jobs.</i>

1359
01:31:06,044 --> 01:31:09,537
<i>Sonsini had known Jobs
since Apple went public in 1980</i>

1360
01:31:09,714 --> 01:31:13,298
<i>and had been a board member at Pixar
when it created a vast program</i>

1361
01:31:13,426 --> 01:31:16,635
<i>of brazenly backdated options
for top executives.</i>

1362
01:31:16,805 --> 01:31:19,593
<i>Yet despite Jobs's long history
with backdating,</i>

1363
01:31:19,724 --> 01:31:23,092
<i>Apple's own investigation,
led by Al Gore,</i>

1364
01:31:23,228 --> 01:31:26,016
<i>absolved Jobs of any wrongdoing.</i>

1365
01:31:26,147 --> 01:31:28,855
<i>Their conclusion was that
Steve Jobs didn't appreciate</i>

1366
01:31:28,984 --> 01:31:31,522
<i>the accounting implications
of the issue.</i>

1367
01:31:31,653 --> 01:31:34,817
I know you're not an accountant,
but do you have an understanding

1368
01:31:34,990 --> 01:31:38,609
as to what generally accepted
accounting principles are?

1369
01:31:38,785 --> 01:31:40,447
Not really.

1370
01:31:40,578 --> 01:31:42,410
<i>Jobs's accounting naiveté</i>

1371
01:31:42,539 --> 01:31:45,407
<i>would be challenged by
his own CFO, Fred Anderson.</i>

1372
01:31:45,542 --> 01:31:48,000
<i>A hero during Apple's comeback,</i>

1373
01:31:48,128 --> 01:31:52,623
<i>Anderson was one exec who
took the fall for backdating.</i>

1374
01:31:52,799 --> 01:31:55,917
As Apple's chief financial officer,
Mr Anderson,

1375
01:31:56,052 --> 01:31:59,295
you had overall responsibility
to ensure that the company

1376
01:31:59,431 --> 01:32:03,095
complied with all financial
reporting requirements, true?

1377
01:32:03,226 --> 01:32:05,343
On advice of council,

1378
01:32:05,478 --> 01:32:09,563
I decline to answer based
on my Fifth Amendment rights.

1379
01:32:09,691 --> 01:32:11,273
<i>When the SEC investigated,</i>

1380
01:32:11,401 --> 01:32:14,610
<i>Apple effectively
threw Anderson under the bus.</i>

1381
01:32:14,779 --> 01:32:17,112
<i>He was forced to resign
from Apple's board</i>

1382
01:32:17,240 --> 01:32:20,404
<i>and to pay $3.6 million in penalties.</i>

1383
01:32:20,535 --> 01:32:24,279
<i>But in a very unusual statement,
Anderson's lawyer made it clear</i>

1384
01:32:24,414 --> 01:32:28,829
<i>that Fred had relied on statements
by Jobs that turned out to be false</i>

1385
01:32:28,960 --> 01:32:32,829
<i>and that Anderson had explained
the dangers of backdating to Jobs.</i>

1386
01:32:32,964 --> 01:32:37,550
Now, this contradicted exactly what
Jobs and the company had maintained

1387
01:32:37,677 --> 01:32:40,215
which was that Steve Jobs didn't
appreciate why this was a problem.

1388
01:32:40,346 --> 01:32:42,929
<i>I think the notion
that Steve Jobs knew nothing</i>

1389
01:32:43,058 --> 01:32:45,596
<i>and Fred Anderson and Nancy Heinen
were entirely responsible</i>

1390
01:32:45,852 --> 01:32:46,852
<i>is ridiculous.</i>

1391
01:32:47,979 --> 01:32:49,345
<i>The company has confirmed</i>

1392
01:32:49,481 --> 01:32:52,474
<i>that Jobs himself
was awarded backdated options</i>

1393
01:32:52,609 --> 01:32:55,602
<i>that carried a false date
in October 2001.</i>

1394
01:32:55,737 --> 01:32:58,571
<i>According to Apple's own report
to the SEC,</i>

1395
01:32:58,698 --> 01:33:03,159
<i>"The award was" improperly recorded
as occurring at a special board meeting</i>

1396
01:33:03,286 --> 01:33:06,870
<i>when in fact such a board meeting
did not occur."</i>

1397
01:33:06,998 --> 01:33:12,960
<i>A fictitious board meeting
that awarded Jobs 7.5 million options.</i>

1398
01:33:13,088 --> 01:33:15,045
<i>Just what was going on?</i>

1399
01:33:15,173 --> 01:33:17,165
<i>At first, all fingers pointed</i>

1400
01:33:17,300 --> 01:33:19,963
<i>to another member
of the Apple comeback team,</i>

1401
01:33:20,095 --> 01:33:21,757
<i>General Counsel Nancy Heinen,</i>

1402
01:33:21,930 --> 01:33:25,514
<i>who had certified the minutes
of the phony board meeting.</i>

1403
01:33:25,642 --> 01:33:28,885
<i>Like Anderson,
Heinen would settle with the SEC</i>

1404
01:33:29,020 --> 01:33:31,683
<i>without admitting or denying guilt.</i>

1405
01:33:31,856 --> 01:33:37,147
<i>But her silence raised questions.
Would she have just decided on her own</i>

1406
01:33:37,278 --> 01:33:41,898
<i>to fake a board meeting
in order to enrich Steve Jobs?</i>

1407
01:33:42,033 --> 01:33:44,070
<i>Who wanted this done?</i>

1408
01:33:45,578 --> 01:33:51,074
As we've seen in the discussions
of the past hour,

1409
01:33:51,209 --> 01:33:55,954
I spent a lot of time trying
to take care of people at Apple

1410
01:33:56,089 --> 01:34:02,962
and to, you know,
surprise and delight them

1411
01:34:03,096 --> 01:34:08,342
with what a career at Apple
could mean to them and their families.

1412
01:34:09,310 --> 01:34:13,350
And I felt that the board wasn't
really doing the same with me.

1413
01:34:13,481 --> 01:34:17,316
- Right.
- So I was...

1414
01:34:20,697 --> 01:34:24,566
hurt, I suppose would be
the most accurate word.

1415
01:34:24,701 --> 01:34:27,990
I'd been working, you know,
I don't know,

1416
01:34:28,121 --> 01:34:30,613
four years, five years of my life,

1417
01:34:30,748 --> 01:34:34,583
and not seeing my family
very much and stuff.

1418
01:34:34,711 --> 01:34:37,169
And I just felt like

1419
01:34:37,297 --> 01:34:40,131
there's nobody looking out
for me here, you know?

1420
01:34:40,258 --> 01:34:41,419
Right. OK.

1421
01:34:41,551 --> 01:34:47,843
So, I wanted them to do something,
and so we talked about it.

1422
01:34:48,016 --> 01:34:51,134
<i>There's no question that
the directives came from him.</i>

1423
01:34:51,269 --> 01:34:53,602
<i>Yet, when the SEC investigated,</i>

1424
01:34:53,730 --> 01:34:56,973
it was as if he was immune.

1425
01:34:58,026 --> 01:35:01,940
I'd wished they'd have come to me
and said,

1426
01:35:02,071 --> 01:35:05,690
"Steve, we've got this new grant
for you,"

1427
01:35:05,825 --> 01:35:08,693
without me having to suggest anything

1428
01:35:08,828 --> 01:35:12,947
or be involved in anything
or negotiate anything.

1429
01:35:13,082 --> 01:35:16,120
That would have been much better
from the company's point of view

1430
01:35:16,252 --> 01:35:23,045
because it would have made me
feel better at that time.

1431
01:35:24,886 --> 01:35:26,673
<i>According to one analyst,</i>

1432
01:35:26,804 --> 01:35:28,761
<i>if Jobs had gone to jail
for backdating,</i>

1433
01:35:28,890 --> 01:35:32,850
<i>the company's value would have
dropped by $22 billion.</i>

1434
01:35:35,521 --> 01:35:37,979
<i>But Jobs was Apple's indispensable man,</i>

1435
01:35:38,107 --> 01:35:43,353
<i>and Apple, Silicon Valley's
indispensable company.</i>

1436
01:35:43,488 --> 01:35:46,981
<i>A cornerstone
of the entire American economy.</i>

1437
01:35:47,116 --> 01:35:49,859
<i>But just how American was Apple?</i>

1438
01:35:51,496 --> 01:35:54,239
Do you swear that the testimony
you're about to give will be...

1439
01:35:54,374 --> 01:35:56,832
<i>When the US Senate
questioned Jobs's successor,</i>

1440
01:35:57,001 --> 01:35:59,493
<i>Tim Cook,
about the company's tax practices,</i>

1441
01:35:59,629 --> 01:36:03,088
<i>many of the subcommittee members
took a moment to state,</i>

1442
01:36:03,216 --> 01:36:08,086
<i>for the record, just how tough
they were willing to be.</i>

1443
01:36:08,221 --> 01:36:13,762
I love Apple, and I'm very proud
of Apple as an American company.

1444
01:36:13,893 --> 01:36:17,307
Apple is an American success story.

1445
01:36:17,522 --> 01:36:22,392
Its products are justifiably well-known
and used throughout the world.

1446
01:36:22,527 --> 01:36:25,861
Just like millions around the world,
I carry an iPhone in my pocket.

1447
01:36:26,030 --> 01:36:27,862
What may not be so well-known

1448
01:36:28,032 --> 01:36:32,402
is that Apple also has a highly
developed tax-avoidance system,

1449
01:36:32,537 --> 01:36:36,577
a system through which it has
amassed more than $100 billion

1450
01:36:36,708 --> 01:36:39,621
in off-shore cash in a tax haven.

1451
01:36:41,796 --> 01:36:45,164
<i>Apple found its tax haven
in the green fields of Ireland</i>

1452
01:36:45,300 --> 01:36:49,294
<i>where Jobs and his team set up
holding companies in the early 1980s.</i>

1453
01:36:49,429 --> 01:36:52,467
<i>The scheme is known as
a "Double Irish".</i>

1454
01:36:53,683 --> 01:36:55,390
<i>Holly Hill industrial estate</i>

1455
01:36:55,518 --> 01:36:58,226
<i>can scarcely be compared
to California's Silicon Valley.</i>

1456
01:36:58,354 --> 01:37:02,564
<i>There is the feeling that Apple of Cork
may become something of a Silicon Hill.</i>

1457
01:37:07,405 --> 01:37:12,946
<i>Today, Apple holds more than
$137 billion of its profits overseas.</i>

1458
01:37:13,119 --> 01:37:18,080
<i>Much of it in two small Irish
companies, one with no employees.</i>

1459
01:37:18,207 --> 01:37:22,372
<i>While the actual cash is held
and invested by New York banks,</i>

1460
01:37:22,503 --> 01:37:26,338
<i>the paper profits are steered
through an office park in Reno, Nevada,</i>

1461
01:37:26,466 --> 01:37:31,257
<i>and then back to the Emerald Isle
where it's taxed at rates less than 1%.</i>

1462
01:37:32,388 --> 01:37:34,596
Senator, we're proud
that all of our R&D,

1463
01:37:34,724 --> 01:37:36,807
or the vast majority of it,
is in the United States.

1464
01:37:36,934 --> 01:37:40,018
I know, but the profits that
result from it are sitting in Ireland

1465
01:37:40,188 --> 01:37:43,852
in corporations that you control
that don't pay taxes.

1466
01:37:44,025 --> 01:37:48,486
Part of the mythology
of these new companies

1467
01:37:48,613 --> 01:37:53,699
<i>was that they in some way reflected
something about America.</i>

1468
01:37:55,119 --> 01:37:58,829
<i>Both Google and Apple
have played on the idea</i>

1469
01:37:58,956 --> 01:38:02,245
<i>of political virtue as part
of selling their company.</i>

1470
01:38:02,377 --> 01:38:09,170
So then to find out they weren't about
political virtue is distressing.

1471
01:38:14,055 --> 01:38:19,016
<i>Steve Jobs said he wanted
to change the world, but into what?</i>

1472
01:38:20,144 --> 01:38:23,763
<i>Companies all over the world
make choices on how to treat workers,</i>

1473
01:38:23,898 --> 01:38:26,891
<i>what to give back
and where to put their money.</i>

1474
01:38:27,026 --> 01:38:29,188
<i>What were Steve's choices?</i>

1475
01:38:29,320 --> 01:38:32,438
<i>In meditation, he found simplicity.</i>

1476
01:38:32,573 --> 01:38:38,194
<i>He loved the idea of "Be Here Now."
But where was "here?"</i>

1477
01:38:39,747 --> 01:38:42,865
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,
we have just landed</i>

1478
01:38:43,000 --> 01:38:46,084
<i>at Beijing International Airport.</i>

1479
01:38:53,469 --> 01:38:56,678
<i>I thought it was important
to cover China</i>

1480
01:38:56,806 --> 01:39:01,267
because Apple has
all of its products made there.

1481
01:39:01,394 --> 01:39:04,307
<i>I mean,
they design their own products,</i>

1482
01:39:04,439 --> 01:39:06,772
<i>but the manufacturing is done in China,</i>

1483
01:39:06,899 --> 01:39:10,768
<i>and so it's caught up in another
country's industrial revolution.</i>

1484
01:39:10,903 --> 01:39:13,646
And a lot of that is
out of Apple's control.

1485
01:39:19,662 --> 01:39:22,700
<i>Four workers died
and 77 were wounded</i>

1486
01:39:22,832 --> 01:39:25,916
<i>in explosions
at two Apple supplier factories</i>

1487
01:39:26,043 --> 01:39:28,126
<i>caused by careless safety procedures.</i>

1488
01:39:29,505 --> 01:39:31,747
<i>The solvents used to sparkle
Apple's touch screens</i>

1489
01:39:31,883 --> 01:39:35,376
<i>were powerful but dangerous,
causing nerve damage</i>

1490
01:39:35,511 --> 01:39:39,425
<i>that led to weakness
and loss of touch in workers.</i>

1491
01:39:39,557 --> 01:39:44,302
<i>They complained about low wages
and pressure to meet Apple's deadlines.</i>

1492
01:39:45,354 --> 01:39:48,142
<i>In the Chinese factories
of many tech companies,</i>

1493
01:39:48,316 --> 01:39:50,273
<i>copper, chromium
and other heavy metals</i>

1494
01:39:50,401 --> 01:39:54,361
<i>saturate the run-off that flows
into local waterways.</i>

1495
01:39:54,489 --> 01:39:56,651
<i>Sometimes chemical levels
are so high</i>

1496
01:39:56,782 --> 01:39:59,616
<i>that sewage treatment plants
can't adequately clean the water</i>

1497
01:39:59,744 --> 01:40:01,827
<i>for it ever to be used again.</i>

1498
01:40:03,915 --> 01:40:09,411
<i>In 2010, Chinese activist Ma Jun
contacted all the tech manufacturers</i>

1499
01:40:09,545 --> 01:40:13,505
<i>to discuss the issue
and even wrote to Jobs personally.</i>

1500
01:40:13,633 --> 01:40:17,923
<i>All the companies ultimately responded
except one. Apple.</i>

1501
01:40:18,054 --> 01:40:20,717
<i>It wasn't until Jobs left the company</i>

1502
01:40:20,848 --> 01:40:24,057
<i>that Apple even agreed
to speak to Ma Jun.</i>

1503
01:40:29,982 --> 01:40:32,269
<i>Foxconn is Apple's top supplier,</i>

1504
01:40:32,401 --> 01:40:36,771
so it all goes downhill from there
in terms of the standards,

1505
01:40:36,906 --> 01:40:38,488
in terms of everything.

1506
01:40:40,535 --> 01:40:43,653
<i>These young people
come from the countryside</i>

1507
01:40:43,788 --> 01:40:49,284
<i>under unimaginably poor conditions,
looking for a better life.</i>

1508
01:40:54,173 --> 01:40:56,916
<i>Sun Danyong, nicknamed Yong,</i>

1509
01:40:57,051 --> 01:40:59,839
<i>came to Foxconn
from a small mountain village.</i>

1510
01:41:02,473 --> 01:41:04,681
<i>Placed in the product
communications department,</i>

1511
01:41:04,809 --> 01:41:08,177
<i>he was responsible for the security
of iPhone prototypes</i>

1512
01:41:08,437 --> 01:41:10,929
<i>bound for Apple's headquarters
in Silicon Valley.</i>

1513
01:41:11,065 --> 01:41:17,357
<i>In 2009, an iPhone 4 prototype
went missing on Yong's watch.</i>

1514
01:41:24,745 --> 01:41:28,489
<i>Sun Danyong was
the first factory worker</i>

1515
01:41:28,624 --> 01:41:31,037
<i>who came under the spotlight.</i>

1516
01:41:31,168 --> 01:41:37,381
What makes his story incredibly vivid
is that in today's day and age,

1517
01:41:37,508 --> 01:41:41,047
there's CCTV cameras recording
where his movements were.

1518
01:41:41,178 --> 01:41:45,798
<i>He had a conversation with his friends
on the Chinese Twitter site,</i>

1519
01:41:45,933 --> 01:41:49,847
and you could really track
what had happened.

1520
01:41:50,855 --> 01:41:53,017
<i>Yong searched
high and low for the prototype</i>

1521
01:41:53,232 --> 01:41:56,396
<i>before reporting it missing
to Foxconn security.</i>

1522
01:41:57,111 --> 01:42:00,275
<i>That evening, officials took him
into an interrogation room</i>

1523
01:42:00,448 --> 01:42:01,905
<i>where he was assaulted</i>

1524
01:42:02,033 --> 01:42:05,617
<i>and was told police would arrive
the next morning to question him.</i>

1525
01:42:06,662 --> 01:42:10,952
<i>Yong was finally permitted
to leave the factory at 10:41pm.</i>

1526
01:42:11,083 --> 01:42:13,450
<i>He wandered to an internet cafe</i>

1527
01:42:13,586 --> 01:42:16,795
<i>where he chatted online
with his friends.</i>

1528
01:42:32,772 --> 01:42:35,640
<i>He logged off
around 1:30 in the morning.</i>

1529
01:42:37,026 --> 01:42:39,894
<i>Soon after, security cameras
spotted him in an elevator</i>

1530
01:42:40,029 --> 01:42:42,817
<i>in his apartment complex.</i>

1531
01:42:42,948 --> 01:42:46,191
<i>He got out on the 12th floor
and texted his girlfriend.</i>

1532
01:43:02,927 --> 01:43:09,720
<i>At 3:33am, security cameras recorded
Sun Danyong jumping to his death.</i>

1533
01:43:15,648 --> 01:43:19,517
<i>Over a period of two years or so,
there were 18 suicides.</i>

1534
01:43:19,652 --> 01:43:24,989
Foxconn set up these nets
to catch people who fall off.

1535
01:43:25,116 --> 01:43:27,403
<i>People were jumping
off of the buildings,</i>

1536
01:43:27,535 --> 01:43:29,822
<i>so they were going to
prevent people from dying</i>

1537
01:43:29,954 --> 01:43:32,992
<i>by having safety nets to catch them.</i>

1538
01:43:38,963 --> 01:43:41,797
You know, they've had,
if you count the attempted suicides,

1539
01:43:41,924 --> 01:43:43,881
13 so far this year.

1540
01:43:44,009 --> 01:43:49,721
And while that is still...
They have 400,000 people at this place.

1541
01:43:49,849 --> 01:43:53,843
So, 13 out of 400,000
is 26 per year so far.

1542
01:43:53,978 --> 01:44:00,100
For 400,000 people or, you know,
let's say seven per 100,000 people,

1543
01:44:00,234 --> 01:44:04,319
that's still under the US suicide rate
of 11 per 100,000 people,

1544
01:44:04,488 --> 01:44:06,104
but it's really troubling.

1545
01:44:06,240 --> 01:44:08,152
Right. It's in one place, too.

1546
01:44:08,284 --> 01:44:10,697
Well, you measure it
by number of people.

1547
01:44:10,911 --> 01:44:14,825
You measure it by numbers of people.
So, we're all over this.

1548
01:44:14,957 --> 01:44:18,701
And it's... It's very troubling.

1549
01:44:18,836 --> 01:44:22,329
So, we're over there trying
to understand what's happening,

1550
01:44:22,506 --> 01:44:24,998
and more importantly,
trying to understand how we can help.

1551
01:44:31,015 --> 01:44:34,725
<i>Apple isn't the only company
to manufacture in China,</i>

1552
01:44:34,894 --> 01:44:38,808
<i>but it is different in one way.
Its enormous profit margin.</i>

1553
01:44:38,939 --> 01:44:43,024
<i>The profit on every iPhone 4
was over $300.</i>

1554
01:44:43,194 --> 01:44:48,110
<i>Yet Apple paid its Chinese workforce
less than $12 per phone.</i>

1555
01:44:48,240 --> 01:44:51,950
<i>If Jobs had really "thought different,"
shouldn't he have cared more</i>

1556
01:44:52,077 --> 01:44:53,909
<i>about the people
who touched the iPhones</i>

1557
01:44:54,038 --> 01:44:58,032
<i>before they appeared in
the hands of Apple's customers?</i>

1558
01:45:06,133 --> 01:45:09,968
<i>When I was writing
critical stories about Apple,</i>

1559
01:45:10,095 --> 01:45:13,259
the mail would be 80% hate mail.

1560
01:45:15,559 --> 01:45:21,146
<i>Even the most reasoned,
judicious criticism</i>

1561
01:45:21,273 --> 01:45:27,395
<i>about labor practices in China,
for crying out loud, it didn't matter.</i>

1562
01:45:27,571 --> 01:45:30,063
<i>People didn't want to hear it.</i>

1563
01:45:30,199 --> 01:45:33,943
<i>They loved this company.
They loved its products.</i>

1564
01:45:34,078 --> 01:45:37,697
<i>They loved the status symbol
of having these things in their hand</i>

1565
01:45:37,832 --> 01:45:41,246
<i>and looking at it all the time,
and it just felt cool,</i>

1566
01:45:41,377 --> 01:45:46,122
<i>and they'd stood in line for two days
to buy one,</i>

1567
01:45:46,257 --> 01:45:48,670
<i>and they didn't want to hear it.</i>

1568
01:45:54,431 --> 01:45:57,765
<i>I was one of those people
who had to have an iPhone.</i>

1569
01:45:57,893 --> 01:46:00,601
<i>I didn't want
to hear about other products,</i>

1570
01:46:00,729 --> 01:46:02,470
<i>and I believed against all reason</i>

1571
01:46:02,648 --> 01:46:06,016
<i>that owning an iPhone made me
part of something better.</i>

1572
01:46:06,151 --> 01:46:09,986
<i>And when it was in my pocket,
for every idle moment,</i>

1573
01:46:10,114 --> 01:46:14,529
<i>my hand was drawn to it,
like Frodo's hand to the ring.</i>

1574
01:46:15,411 --> 01:46:18,404
<i>The real magic of it
is that these myths</i>

1575
01:46:18,539 --> 01:46:24,001
<i>are surrounding a company
that makes phones.</i>

1576
01:46:25,504 --> 01:46:27,917
A phone is not a mythical device.

1577
01:46:29,091 --> 01:46:31,083
Um...

1578
01:46:31,218 --> 01:46:38,842
And it sort of makes you wonder
less about Apple than about us.

1579
01:46:40,561 --> 01:46:43,850
<i>The myth-making
around technology in general</i>

1580
01:46:43,981 --> 01:46:50,854
<i>allows the technologist to do things
that would be viewed as heinous</i>

1581
01:46:50,988 --> 01:46:54,152
<i>if they were done
by other kinds of companies.</i>

1582
01:46:56,160 --> 01:46:58,402
<i>This is a story that's amazing.</i>

1583
01:46:58,537 --> 01:47:03,032
<i>It's got theft, it's got buying
stolen property, it's got extortion.</i>

1584
01:47:03,167 --> 01:47:05,830
I'm sure there's sex
in there somewhere, you know?

1585
01:47:05,961 --> 01:47:07,327
Really?

1586
01:47:07,463 --> 01:47:10,456
So somebody should make
a movie out of this.

1587
01:47:10,591 --> 01:47:13,049
<i>If you were to make a movie
about it,</i>

1588
01:47:13,177 --> 01:47:16,670
<i>the first scene would be set in
a beer garden in Silicon Valley.</i>

1589
01:47:16,805 --> 01:47:19,593
<i>As he swilled a few steins of Pilsner,</i>

1590
01:47:19,767 --> 01:47:23,226
<i>Apple's Gray Powell was testing out
a new iPhone prototype.</i>

1591
01:47:25,105 --> 01:47:28,598
<i>But when Powell staggered
out of the bar, he forgot one thing.</i>

1592
01:47:28,776 --> 01:47:30,517
<i>The iPhone.</i>

1593
01:47:30,694 --> 01:47:35,814
<i>It was found on a bar stool
by a college student named Brian Hogan.</i>

1594
01:47:37,159 --> 01:47:39,071
<i>And this e-mail
comes into our tip box,</i>

1595
01:47:39,203 --> 01:47:43,538
and there was this guy claiming
that he had this new iPhone prototype.

1596
01:47:43,707 --> 01:47:47,872
<i>Getting inside Apple's security fort,</i>

1597
01:47:48,003 --> 01:47:50,461
<i>and look at something
that is under wrap.</i>

1598
01:47:50,589 --> 01:47:54,424
But back then, when Steve Jobs was
at the helm and in his full power,

1599
01:47:54,551 --> 01:47:56,543
it was impossible
to get anything from them.

1600
01:47:56,720 --> 01:47:58,632
It was incredibly exciting.

1601
01:47:58,806 --> 01:48:01,719
At that point, Apple didn't have
a whole lot of leaks.

1602
01:48:01,850 --> 01:48:04,843
And then I go to Nick and I say,

1603
01:48:04,979 --> 01:48:08,063
"We think it's the real thing,
and they want their money."

1604
01:48:08,190 --> 01:48:10,182
And Nick said, "Anything you want."

1605
01:48:10,317 --> 01:48:14,106
For us, there's no question
as to whether we write the story or not.

1606
01:48:14,238 --> 01:48:17,402
That's what was so disturbing,
I think, to Steve Jobs,

1607
01:48:17,533 --> 01:48:19,775
was that he'd been used to having

1608
01:48:19,910 --> 01:48:22,323
a much more controlled
relationship with the press.

1609
01:48:22,454 --> 01:48:25,162
Our plan was to take pictures of it,

1610
01:48:25,290 --> 01:48:28,499
write about it,
and then return it back to Apple.

1611
01:48:28,627 --> 01:48:31,165
Hey, I'm Jason Chen.
This is the new iPhone.

1612
01:48:31,296 --> 01:48:33,333
Here are some of the new features.

1613
01:48:33,465 --> 01:48:36,879
<i>In the beginning, it was OK.
Only nerds looking at it, I guess.</i>

1614
01:48:37,011 --> 01:48:38,422
And then the story
started to pick up.

1615
01:48:40,514 --> 01:48:43,848
You know, it was the biggest
scoop in tech in history.

1616
01:48:46,228 --> 01:48:49,312
"Hi, this is Steve Jobs.
I want my phone back."

1617
01:48:49,440 --> 01:48:51,557
And it was
in a really charming voice.

1618
01:48:51,692 --> 01:48:55,936
And it's same way you'd ask for,
you know, a hat you'd lent a friend.

1619
01:48:56,071 --> 01:49:00,782
<i>I'd met him a couple of times before.
It was his voice, unmistakably.</i>

1620
01:49:00,909 --> 01:49:02,400
He said, "You know, I'm not mad at you."

1621
01:49:02,536 --> 01:49:04,573
"It's someone we worked with
who lost it."

1622
01:49:04,705 --> 01:49:06,697
"But you've had your fun,
and we need this phone back

1623
01:49:06,874 --> 01:49:08,490
before it gets into the wrong hands."

1624
01:49:08,625 --> 01:49:12,118
And at that point, I was thinking,
"Isn't it already in the wrong hands?"

1625
01:49:17,551 --> 01:49:21,886
Nick at that moment said,
"Ask for a letter."

1626
01:49:22,014 --> 01:49:24,006
"Ask for an official letter
asking for it."

1627
01:49:24,141 --> 01:49:26,679
"We need the actual confirmation
that this is the real thing."

1628
01:49:26,894 --> 01:49:29,932
<i>The next call,
he said he didn't want to claim it.</i>

1629
01:49:30,064 --> 01:49:32,226
<i>He really changed his tone
at that point,</i>

1630
01:49:32,357 --> 01:49:34,974
<i>because it would affect
the sales of the current model,</i>

1631
01:49:35,194 --> 01:49:36,901
which is kind of disappointing,
you know?

1632
01:49:37,029 --> 01:49:39,521
You hear all these stories about
this guy not caring about money.

1633
01:49:39,656 --> 01:49:42,069
<i>And he goes,
"This is some serious shit."</i>

1634
01:49:42,201 --> 01:49:45,114
<i>"If I have to serve you papers,
I'm coming for something,</i>

1635
01:49:45,245 --> 01:49:48,079
<i>and it's going to mean someone in your
organization is going to go to jail."</i>

1636
01:49:48,207 --> 01:49:51,291
For a reporter who's got a chip
on his shoulder against corporations,

1637
01:49:51,418 --> 01:49:55,037
that's like,
"Martyr me. Please, martyr me."

1638
01:49:55,172 --> 01:49:59,257
"I'll go to jail for an iPhone.
Like, really."

1639
01:49:59,384 --> 01:50:03,219
<i>He called back later and he said,
"OK, we'll get you the letter,"</i>

1640
01:50:03,347 --> 01:50:05,555
<i>and he was just resigned and cold.</i>

1641
01:50:05,682 --> 01:50:08,720
<i>So, they sent us the letter,
and they sent a lawyer from Apple</i>

1642
01:50:08,894 --> 01:50:11,227
to Jason's house to pick up the phone.

1643
01:50:11,355 --> 01:50:13,563
It was a very cold exchange.

1644
01:50:13,732 --> 01:50:16,270
He said, "I believe you have
something of mine," or something.

1645
01:50:16,401 --> 01:50:19,485
And I handed it to him, and he said,
"Thank you very much," and he left.

1646
01:50:19,613 --> 01:50:22,481
Was that the end of it,
as far as Apple was concerned?

1647
01:50:22,616 --> 01:50:23,948
No, of course not.

1648
01:50:24,076 --> 01:50:27,695
Then all the nightmares started.

1649
01:50:54,773 --> 01:50:58,517
The cops had to bash in the guy's door?

1650
01:50:58,652 --> 01:51:01,941
Don't they know there's an app for that?

1651
01:51:02,072 --> 01:51:04,439
<i>Anyone who'd worked
with Jobs before</i>

1652
01:51:04,575 --> 01:51:07,693
would know of other instances
where he'd been a bully.

1653
01:51:07,828 --> 01:51:10,616
But this was probably
the most public evidence of bullying.

1654
01:51:11,832 --> 01:51:15,451
<i>My wife and I went out for dinner.
We came back home,</i>

1655
01:51:15,586 --> 01:51:18,124
<i>and we noticed the garage door
was slightly opened.</i>

1656
01:51:18,255 --> 01:51:21,623
You know, and I was wondering,
"What's going on?"

1657
01:51:21,758 --> 01:51:24,501
<i>And I opened it all the way,
and I noticed there were people inside.</i>

1658
01:51:24,678 --> 01:51:28,171
<i>And I thought, you know,
"Holy crap, I'm being robbed."</i>

1659
01:51:28,307 --> 01:51:30,765
And then I looked closer
and realized it was cops.

1660
01:51:33,061 --> 01:51:35,769
<i>The cops seized boxes
of Chen's personal property</i>

1661
01:51:35,939 --> 01:51:38,682
<i>including four computers,
two cellphones</i>

1662
01:51:38,817 --> 01:51:41,400
<i>and a box of his business cards.</i>

1663
01:51:43,155 --> 01:51:48,196
<i>For the Gizmodo movie, this raised
questions of plot and motivation.</i>

1664
01:51:48,327 --> 01:51:53,243
<i>Why break down Chen's door
after he returned the iPhone?</i>

1665
01:51:53,373 --> 01:51:57,413
<i>They showed me the warrant
to search the premises and said,</i>

1666
01:51:57,544 --> 01:51:59,331
"We're part of the REACT team."

1667
01:51:59,463 --> 01:52:02,581
<i>After they searched the house,
obviously I went and Googled it.</i>

1668
01:52:02,716 --> 01:52:04,753
<i>The officers
who raided Chen's apartment</i>

1669
01:52:04,885 --> 01:52:08,424
<i>were part of a little-known criminal
task force called REACT,</i>

1670
01:52:08,555 --> 01:52:11,764
<i>composed of local, state
and federal officials</i>

1671
01:52:11,892 --> 01:52:15,385
<i>on the lookout for corporate espionage
in Silicon Valley.</i>

1672
01:52:17,397 --> 01:52:20,310
My initial response was,
"This is cool. It's Apple."

1673
01:52:21,401 --> 01:52:23,188
<i>Chris Feasel was the deputy DA</i>

1674
01:52:23,320 --> 01:52:25,858
<i>advising REACT on the case.</i>

1675
01:52:26,031 --> 01:52:28,023
<i>After the raid on Chen's apartment,</i>

1676
01:52:28,158 --> 01:52:31,492
<i>Feasel was received at Apple
by Jobs himself.</i>

1677
01:52:31,620 --> 01:52:35,660
He was very, very nice,
very high-energy.

1678
01:52:36,625 --> 01:52:39,709
<i>We had a back-and-forth about
what he wanted to see happen</i>

1679
01:52:39,836 --> 01:52:42,328
<i>versus what some of the realities were
about doing a prosecution.</i>

1680
01:52:42,464 --> 01:52:46,583
He was very supportive about whatever
choices that we made on the case.

1681
01:52:46,718 --> 01:52:48,755
Where do people
come down on this?

1682
01:52:48,887 --> 01:52:51,800
- Where do you come down on it?
- Well, I can just tell you what...

1683
01:52:51,932 --> 01:52:58,270
There is an ongoing investigation
by the DA, and I'm not current on it.

1684
01:52:58,397 --> 01:53:01,936
He was very involved in it
and very interested in it

1685
01:53:02,067 --> 01:53:03,649
and wanted to be kept abreast

1686
01:53:03,777 --> 01:53:06,019
about what was going on
in the investigation.

1687
01:53:06,947 --> 01:53:10,440
<i>Jobs had every reason to
expect that he would be kept informed</i>

1688
01:53:10,575 --> 01:53:13,613
<i>because REACT wasn't
a purely government agency.</i>

1689
01:53:13,745 --> 01:53:15,077
<i>It had a steering committee</i>

1690
01:53:15,247 --> 01:53:19,207
<i>composed of many of the major
companies in the Valley.</i>

1691
01:53:19,376 --> 01:53:22,790
<i>In a town so completely dominated
by the tech industry,</i>

1692
01:53:22,921 --> 01:53:25,288
<i>had law enforcement become the muscle</i>

1693
01:53:25,424 --> 01:53:27,837
<i>for the largest corporations
in the world?</i>

1694
01:53:31,263 --> 01:53:38,352
<i>He was very, very adamant
and very passionate about his creation.</i>

1695
01:53:38,478 --> 01:53:42,142
And the only analogy I can think of is
if somebody stole your baby,

1696
01:53:42,316 --> 01:53:44,182
you would be very upset about it.

1697
01:53:44,401 --> 01:53:48,862
<i>That's how Mr Jobs felt.
Somebody had taken his baby.</i>

1698
01:53:51,366 --> 01:53:53,323
<i>In spite of pressure from Apple,</i>

1699
01:53:53,452 --> 01:53:56,445
<i>the DA decided
not to pursue the charges against Chen</i>

1700
01:53:56,580 --> 01:53:59,243
<i>because he hadn't received
stolen property.</i>

1701
01:53:59,374 --> 01:54:01,582
<i>He was a journalist doing a story.</i>

1702
01:54:02,961 --> 01:54:06,796
When this whole thing
with Gizmodo happened,

1703
01:54:06,923 --> 01:54:11,714
I got a lot of advice
from people that said,

1704
01:54:11,845 --> 01:54:18,137
"You shouldn't go after a journalist
because they bought stolen property,

1705
01:54:18,268 --> 01:54:22,558
and they tried to extort you.
You should let it slide."

1706
01:54:22,689 --> 01:54:27,104
"Apple's a big company now.
You don't want the PR."

1707
01:54:27,235 --> 01:54:29,192
"You should let it slide."

1708
01:54:29,321 --> 01:54:34,487
And I thought deeply about this,
and I ended up concluding

1709
01:54:34,618 --> 01:54:37,702
that the worst thing
that could possibly happen

1710
01:54:37,829 --> 01:54:42,324
as we get big and we get
a little more influence in the world,

1711
01:54:42,459 --> 01:54:48,877
is if we change our core values
and start letting it slide.

1712
01:54:49,049 --> 01:54:53,214
I can't do that. I'd rather quit.

1713
01:54:54,304 --> 01:54:57,342
<i>What values
was Jobs talking about?</i>

1714
01:54:57,474 --> 01:55:02,469
<i>When Apple was taking on IBM,
it was David versus Goliath.</i>

1715
01:55:02,646 --> 01:55:08,017
<i>But when Apple became Goliath,
to whom was Jobs giving the finger?</i>

1716
01:55:12,656 --> 01:55:17,492
<i>The sad thing is that how many
months did he have left after that?</i>

1717
01:55:17,619 --> 01:55:22,990
This was a guy who knew,
who knew at the time,

1718
01:55:23,166 --> 01:55:30,164
he was dying, and he dedicated,
what, ten minutes of his life

1719
01:55:30,298 --> 01:55:33,336
to talk about these guys
who found a phone in a bar

1720
01:55:33,468 --> 01:55:38,259
and then published a story about it?
Isn't that a little bit strange?

1721
01:55:41,435 --> 01:55:45,019
My third story is about death.

1722
01:55:46,064 --> 01:55:50,058
About a year ago,
I was diagnosed with cancer.

1723
01:55:50,235 --> 01:55:52,227
I had a scan at 7:30 in the morning,

1724
01:55:52,362 --> 01:55:55,446
and it clearly showed
a tumor on my pancreas.

1725
01:55:55,574 --> 01:55:57,566
I didn't even know
what a pancreas was.

1726
01:55:57,701 --> 01:55:59,283
The doctors told me

1727
01:55:59,411 --> 01:56:03,405
this was almost certainly
a type of cancer that is incurable,

1728
01:56:03,540 --> 01:56:07,625
and that I should expect to live
no longer than three to six months.

1729
01:56:07,752 --> 01:56:12,338
My doctor advised me to go home
and get my affairs in order,

1730
01:56:12,507 --> 01:56:15,841
which is doctor's code
for "prepare to die."

1731
01:56:15,969 --> 01:56:17,756
It means to try and tell your kids

1732
01:56:17,888 --> 01:56:21,723
everything you thought you'd have
the next ten years to tell them

1733
01:56:21,850 --> 01:56:23,307
in just a few months.

1734
01:56:23,435 --> 01:56:28,601
I lived with that diagnosis all day.
Later that evening, I had a biopsy.

1735
01:56:28,732 --> 01:56:32,066
I was sedated, but my wife,
who was there,

1736
01:56:32,277 --> 01:56:35,441
told me that when they viewed the cells
under a microscope,

1737
01:56:35,572 --> 01:56:38,280
the doctors started crying
because it turned out to be

1738
01:56:38,408 --> 01:56:42,743
a very rare form of pancreatic cancer
that is curable with surgery.

1739
01:56:42,871 --> 01:56:46,490
I had the surgery
and, thankfully, I'm fine now.

1740
01:56:50,128 --> 01:56:52,836
<i>Steve Jobs talked about
his cancer very emotionally</i>

1741
01:56:52,964 --> 01:56:56,548
<i>at the Stanford graduation ceremony
in 2005.</i>

1742
01:56:56,676 --> 01:56:58,668
And he very clearly told the story

1743
01:56:58,803 --> 01:57:01,341
to make it sound as though
he had been diagnosed

1744
01:57:01,515 --> 01:57:04,303
and moved immediately to surgery,
and been cured.

1745
01:57:04,434 --> 01:57:05,720
That simply wasn't true.

1746
01:57:05,852 --> 01:57:09,436
<i>What I found out, over a period
of months of reporting,</i>

1747
01:57:09,564 --> 01:57:12,307
<i>was that Steve Jobs actually
had been diagnosed with cancer</i>

1748
01:57:12,442 --> 01:57:16,186
<i>nine months earlier, and that
for a period of nine months,</i>

1749
01:57:16,363 --> 01:57:19,822
<i>he had refused to have the surgery
that every medical expert said</i>

1750
01:57:19,950 --> 01:57:22,613
<i>was necessary to increase
his prospects for survival.</i>

1751
01:57:22,744 --> 01:57:24,736
Instead of having the surgery,

1752
01:57:24,871 --> 01:57:28,581
he had sought
alternative medicine approaches

1753
01:57:28,708 --> 01:57:30,791
to try to cure himself of cancer.

1754
01:57:31,962 --> 01:57:34,705
<i>Entrepreneurs have
an almost pathological need</i>

1755
01:57:34,839 --> 01:57:36,751
<i>to control their own fate.</i>

1756
01:57:36,883 --> 01:57:38,169
<i>They'll take any suffering</i>

1757
01:57:38,301 --> 01:57:40,133
if they can just be in charge
of their destiny

1758
01:57:40,303 --> 01:57:42,295
and not have it
in somebody else's hands.

1759
01:57:42,430 --> 01:57:47,516
<i>Apple's stock has been
volatile on rumors about Jobs's health.</i>

1760
01:57:47,644 --> 01:57:49,852
The company's stock
was halted for a time,

1761
01:57:49,980 --> 01:57:53,690
then took a big hit when it re-opened
in after-hours trading.

1762
01:57:53,817 --> 01:57:55,774
<i>Apple's share prices have dropped</i>

1763
01:57:55,902 --> 01:57:58,815
<i>with every pound
that Jobs has lost in recent months.</i>

1764
01:58:00,198 --> 01:58:02,656
<i>Apple really landed
into a dicey situation</i>

1765
01:58:02,784 --> 01:58:04,616
<i>when Steve decided
to issue a letter saying,</i>

1766
01:58:04,744 --> 01:58:06,610
<i>"Well, you know,
nothing's wrong with me."</i>

1767
01:58:06,746 --> 01:58:09,238
"It's just a minor problem,"
And it wasn't a minor problem.

1768
01:58:10,667 --> 01:58:14,160
<i>Steve Jobs made a point
of withholding from the world</i>

1769
01:58:14,337 --> 01:58:16,795
<i>that he faced this illness.</i>

1770
01:58:16,923 --> 01:58:18,710
<i>That's something
investors want to know,</i>

1771
01:58:18,842 --> 01:58:20,549
<i>because when you
bought Apple stock then,</i>

1772
01:58:20,719 --> 01:58:22,631
you were buying into Steve Jobs.

1773
01:58:22,804 --> 01:58:26,218
He was obligated
to tell shareholders right away

1774
01:58:26,349 --> 01:58:27,840
about this serious illness.

1775
01:58:29,019 --> 01:58:31,727
<i>You do personally
want to give Steve the privacy,</i>

1776
01:58:31,855 --> 01:58:34,814
<i>but Steve put the spotlight on him,</i>

1777
01:58:34,941 --> 01:58:38,730
and you can't turn that off
just because it's inconvenient.

1778
01:58:41,615 --> 01:58:44,358
<i>After the story came out,
I saw Steve.</i>

1779
01:58:44,492 --> 01:58:47,075
He started talking about Apple,
and he said,

1780
01:58:47,203 --> 01:58:51,447
<i>"You know, Apple is really a company
that doesn't have any divisions."</i>

1781
01:58:51,583 --> 01:58:53,700
<i>"We don't have all this bureaucracy."</i>

1782
01:58:53,835 --> 01:58:56,748
And I said, "Steve, that would be
a great story for <i>Fortune."</i>

1783
01:58:56,880 --> 01:59:02,501
And he looked at me, and he said,
"No."

1784
01:59:02,636 --> 01:59:08,382
"I don't think we can do that story
with you. Not now."

1785
01:59:09,976 --> 01:59:11,592
"Not now."

1786
01:59:11,811 --> 01:59:15,725
And then he said,
and the whole room went quiet,

1787
01:59:15,857 --> 01:59:19,817
and he said, "you know, we used to..."

1788
01:59:21,154 --> 01:59:24,693
"We used to really be friends
with <i>Fortune,</i>

1789
01:59:24,824 --> 01:59:31,788
I used to be friends with <i>Fortune,</i>
but not anymore. Not anymore."

1790
01:59:31,915 --> 01:59:35,454
And then I remember these tears
came out of his eyes,

1791
01:59:35,585 --> 01:59:37,042
and one was on his glasses,

1792
01:59:37,170 --> 01:59:41,665
and then one, I remember it rolling
off his cheek and hitting his shirt,

1793
01:59:41,800 --> 01:59:46,841
and he was just crying,
and the whole room was silent.

1794
01:59:48,890 --> 01:59:52,600
Apple CEO Steve Jobs today
made his first public appearance

1795
01:59:52,727 --> 01:59:54,593
since getting a new liver
five months ago.

1796
01:59:54,729 --> 01:59:55,845
<i>For the first time,</i>

1797
01:59:55,980 --> 01:59:58,893
<i>the 54-year-old CEO
publicly acknowledged</i>

1798
01:59:59,025 --> 02:00:02,484
<i>the liver transplant this spring
that saved his life.</i>

1799
02:00:02,612 --> 02:00:08,233
Well, I now have the liver
of a mid-20s person.

1800
02:00:11,871 --> 02:00:16,491
I'd like to take a moment and thank
everybody in the Apple community

1801
02:00:16,626 --> 02:00:20,836
for the heartfelt support I got, too.
It really meant a lot.

1802
02:00:20,964 --> 02:00:25,834
And I'd also like
to especially thank Tim Cook

1803
02:00:25,969 --> 02:00:29,679
and the entire executive team of Apple.

1804
02:00:29,806 --> 02:00:32,219
They really rose to the occasion

1805
02:00:32,350 --> 02:00:36,469
and ran the company very ably
in that difficult period.

1806
02:00:36,604 --> 02:00:38,937
So, thank you, guys.
Let's give them a round of applause.

1807
02:00:40,483 --> 02:00:42,065
<i>He loved what he did.</i>

1808
02:00:42,193 --> 02:00:44,230
I do have an e-mail from him
saying that.

1809
02:00:44,362 --> 02:00:46,854
<i>He said, you know,
"Both of us were fortunate," he said,</i>

1810
02:00:46,990 --> 02:00:49,357
<i>in that we loved what we did</i>

1811
02:00:49,534 --> 02:00:52,277
<i>and we were able to do it
for a long time.</i>

1812
02:00:52,412 --> 02:00:54,825
<i>And he said,
"What else could you ask for?"</i>

1813
02:00:56,207 --> 02:01:00,918
We're maybe a little more experienced,
certainly more beat-up,

1814
02:01:01,045 --> 02:01:04,755
but the core values are the same.

1815
02:01:04,883 --> 02:01:09,503
I don't see why you have to change
if you get big.

1816
02:01:09,679 --> 02:01:11,887
<i>Straightforward to me.</i>

1817
02:01:12,015 --> 02:01:14,348
<i>Apple was big.</i>

1818
02:01:14,517 --> 02:01:18,807
<i>By this time, one of the biggest
corporations in the world.</i>

1819
02:01:21,274 --> 02:01:24,858
<i>But each time we saw Jobs,
he seemed smaller.</i>

1820
02:01:28,364 --> 02:01:32,278
<i>As his devices got stronger,
Jobs got weaker.</i>

1821
02:01:32,410 --> 02:01:35,903
It's so much more intimate
than a laptop,

1822
02:01:36,039 --> 02:01:39,282
and it's so much more capable
than a smartphone

1823
02:01:39,417 --> 02:01:41,249
with this gorgeous, large display.

1824
02:01:41,377 --> 02:01:45,166
<i>I think that a lot of the grief
at Jobs's death</i>

1825
02:01:45,298 --> 02:01:50,464
was a fear that we had been
very comfortable

1826
02:01:50,637 --> 02:01:52,970
<i>for the last decade in his hands.</i>

1827
02:01:53,097 --> 02:01:57,762
It's phenomenal to hold the internet
in your hand.

1828
02:01:57,894 --> 02:02:00,181
<i>That he was going to keep
doing these amazing things.</i>

1829
02:02:00,313 --> 02:02:04,273
Now he's gone, and there's no indication
that anyone's going to replace him.

1830
02:02:36,975 --> 02:02:38,716
Welcome.

1831
02:02:44,691 --> 02:02:46,057
Thank you.

1832
02:02:58,454 --> 02:03:00,161
Thank you very much.

1833
02:03:03,960 --> 02:03:05,542
- It always helps...
- We love you!

1834
02:03:05,712 --> 02:03:09,296
Thank you.

1835
02:03:09,507 --> 02:03:12,796
It always helps,
and I appreciate it very much.

1836
02:03:12,927 --> 02:03:16,841
<i>He resigned officially
in August. Two weeks earlier,</i>

1837
02:03:16,973 --> 02:03:20,466
<i>Apple had become the highest-valued
corporation on Earth.</i>

1838
02:03:20,643 --> 02:03:22,259
And thank you for coming so much.

1839
02:03:22,395 --> 02:03:24,978
<i>We've got a great week
planned for you.</i>

1840
02:03:49,923 --> 02:03:52,916
<i>This is a field
where one does not write a principia</i>

1841
02:03:53,051 --> 02:03:55,634
<i>which holds up for 200 years</i>

1842
02:03:55,762 --> 02:03:58,095
<i>or paints a painting that'll be
looked at for centuries,</i>

1843
02:03:58,222 --> 02:04:01,932
<i>or builds a church
that will be admired</i>

1844
02:04:02,060 --> 02:04:03,972
<i>and looked at in astonishment
for centuries.</i>

1845
02:04:04,103 --> 02:04:06,436
No, this is a field
where one does one's work,

1846
02:04:06,564 --> 02:04:08,476
and in ten years, it's obsolete

1847
02:04:08,608 --> 02:04:11,225
and really will not be useable
within ten or 20 years.

1848
02:04:11,361 --> 02:04:13,273
I mean, you can't go back
and use an Apple I,

1849
02:04:13,404 --> 02:04:14,565
cos there's no software for it.

1850
02:04:14,739 --> 02:04:17,197
In another ten years or so,
you won't be able to use an Apple II.

1851
02:04:17,325 --> 02:04:19,783
You won't even be able to fire it up
and see what it was like.

1852
02:04:21,537 --> 02:04:24,996
<i>It's sort of like
sediment of rocks.</i>

1853
02:04:25,124 --> 02:04:26,831
<i>You're building up a mountain,</i>

1854
02:04:26,960 --> 02:04:30,124
<i>and you get to contribute
your little layer of sedimentary rock</i>

1855
02:04:30,254 --> 02:04:32,246
<i>to make the mountain that much higher.</i>

1856
02:04:32,382 --> 02:04:35,966
<i>But no one on the surface will,
unless they have x-ray vision,</i>

1857
02:04:36,135 --> 02:04:37,842
<i>will see your sediment.</i>

1858
02:04:41,265 --> 02:04:44,679
<i>In Japan, there's
an idea called "mono no aware,"</i>

1859
02:04:44,811 --> 02:04:48,145
<i>meaning "the deep awareness of things".</i>

1860
02:04:48,272 --> 02:04:51,231
<i>It celebrates the melancholy
of the passing of life</i>

1861
02:04:51,359 --> 02:04:55,148
<i>and sees more beauty in the fallen leaf
than the one on the branch.</i>

1862
02:04:56,406 --> 02:04:59,319
<i>Maybe that's what Japan held for Jobs.</i>

1863
02:04:59,450 --> 02:05:04,320
<i>The sadness of the soul
as expressed in the beauty of things.</i>

1864
02:05:09,252 --> 02:05:11,869
<i>In the end, I was left
with the same question</i>

1865
02:05:12,005 --> 02:05:13,541
<i>with which I began this journey.</i>

1866
02:05:13,673 --> 02:05:18,213
<i>"Why did so many strangers weep
for Steve Jobs?"</i>

1867
02:05:18,344 --> 02:05:21,633
<i>It's too simple to say it was
because he gave us products we love</i>

1868
02:05:21,806 --> 02:05:25,675
<i>without asking why we love them
the way we do.</i>

1869
02:05:25,852 --> 02:05:28,060
<i>It's too simple even to conclude
that we love them</i>

1870
02:05:28,229 --> 02:05:30,346
<i>because they connect us
to a wider world</i>

1871
02:05:30,481 --> 02:05:33,599
<i>and the people in our lives
that are far away,</i>

1872
02:05:33,776 --> 02:05:37,110
<i>because these machines isolate us, too.</i>

1873
02:05:39,699 --> 02:05:43,568
<i>Perhaps the contradictory nature
of our experience with these gadgets</i>

1874
02:05:43,703 --> 02:05:46,286
<i>mirrors the contradictions
in Jobs himself.</i>

1875
02:05:48,666 --> 02:05:52,706
<i>He was an artist who sought perfection,
but could never find peace.</i>

1876
02:05:54,964 --> 02:05:58,833
<i>He had the focus of a monk,
but none of the empathy.</i>

1877
02:06:01,095 --> 02:06:04,805
<i>He offered us freedom,
but only within a closed garden,</i>

1878
02:06:04,932 --> 02:06:07,049
<i>to which he held the key.</i>

1879
02:06:11,314 --> 02:06:13,306
<i>To reconcile these contradictions,</i>

1880
02:06:13,441 --> 02:06:17,185
<i>I think we have to look to the other
half of our relationship with Jobs.</i>

1881
02:06:17,320 --> 02:06:18,982
<i>To ourselves.</i>

1882
02:06:22,241 --> 02:06:26,451
<i>As Jobs wanted it,
the screen of my iPhone is dark.</i>

1883
02:06:26,621 --> 02:06:29,204
<i>A Zen landscape of the unseen.</i>

1884
02:06:29,332 --> 02:06:34,293
<i>If I stare into it, I see
an obscure reflection of myself,</i>

1885
02:06:34,420 --> 02:06:37,037
<i>but this impression
lasts just a fleeting moment</i>

1886
02:06:37,173 --> 02:06:40,757
<i>before I press the home key
and the screen lights up.</i>

1887
02:06:40,927 --> 02:06:44,762
<i>But perhaps I should spend a moment
regarding that reflection,</i>

1888
02:06:44,931 --> 02:06:50,928
<i>asking myself what, in buying
and using this product, I am doing?</i>

1889
02:06:51,062 --> 02:06:53,554
<i>What is the full nature
of my transaction</i>

1890
02:06:53,731 --> 02:06:58,146
<i>with the maker of this magical
and intimate machine?</i>

1891
02:07:18,798 --> 02:07:24,965
<i>♪ Once I wanted to be the greatest</i>

1892
02:07:25,096 --> 02:07:27,383
<i>♪ Greatest, greatest, greatest</i>

1893
02:07:27,515 --> 02:07:33,352
<i>♪ No wind or waterfall could stall me</i>

1894
02:07:34,772 --> 02:07:40,439
<i>♪ And then came the rush of the flood</i>

1895
02:07:40,611 --> 02:07:45,823
<i>♪ Stars at night turned deep to dust</i>

1896
02:07:45,992 --> 02:07:51,454
<i>♪ Melt me down into big, black armor</i>

1897
02:07:54,542 --> 02:08:01,460
<i>♪ Leave no trace of grace
Just in your honor</i>

1898
02:08:03,676 --> 02:08:09,388
<i>♪ Lower me down to culprit south</i>

1899
02:08:09,515 --> 02:08:13,099
<i>♪ Make 'em wash a space in town</i>

1900
02:08:13,227 --> 02:08:17,221
<i>♪ For the lead and the dregs of my bed</i>

1901
02:08:17,356 --> 02:08:20,815
<i>♪ I've been sleeping</i>

1902
02:08:20,985 --> 02:08:23,819
<i>♪ Lower me down</i>

1903
02:08:23,988 --> 02:08:28,323
<i>♪ Pin me in, secure the grounds</i>

1904
02:08:30,369 --> 02:08:31,985
<i>♪ For the later parade</i>

